(1, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 13:37:37', '2016-05-28 13:37:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Law', 'Law is comprised of a body of rules governing action or conduct prescribed by controlling authority with binding legal force. The law may be derived from constitutional, statutory, or case law sources. Administrative agencies may also promulgate regulations or orders which may have the force and effect of law.\r\nKey Words or Phrases:\r\n1. law\r\n2. body of rules governing action or conduct\r\n3. controlling authority\r\n4. binding legal force\r\n5. constitutional\r\n6. statutory \r\n7. case law\r\n8. administrative regulations', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(2, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:18:48', '2016-05-28 14:18:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'American Law Institute', 'The American Law Institute is an organization of American legal scholars responsible for developing â€œRestatementsâ€ of the law for numerous legal disciplines. The American Law Institute, in conjunction with the National Conference of commissioners, also assists with the development of uniform state laws.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. American Law Institute\n2. American legal scholars\n3. Restatements of the Law\n4. Uniform State Laws', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(3, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:24:00', '2016-05-28 14:24:00', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Restatements of Law', 'The American Law Institute has authored a series of legal volumes which explain existing law in a general area, such as torts and contracts, and also explain how the law in this area is changing, as well as scholarly opinions regarding how the law should be developed in the future. The Restatements have had significant impact on shaping the disciplines of the law covered.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. American Law Institute authored series of legal volumes\n2. existing law\n3. current trends changing in law\n4. scholarly opinions regarding how law should develop', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(4, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:27:38', '2016-05-28 14:27:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Jurisprudence', 'The science of law which functions to ascertain principles on which legal rules are based. Jurisprudence is not concerned with morality or politics; instead, jurisprudence is concerned with the ultimate effects produced when legal rules are applied to society\\''s members collectively. Jurisprudence has also been referred to as the philosophy of law.\nKey Words or Phrases\n1. science of law\n2. functions to ascertain principles on which legal rules are based\n3. not concerned with morality or politics\n4. concerned with ultimate effects upon society from application of legal rules\n5. philosophy of law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(5, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:28:22', '2016-05-28 14:28:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Constitution of the United States', 'The Constitution of the United States is the fundamental law of the nation which establishes the character, conception, and power of our federal government. Constitutional law is the supreme law of the land.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. fundamental law of the nation\n2. establishes character, conception and power of federal government\n3. supreme law of the land', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(6, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:52:32', '2016-05-28 14:52:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Advocacy', 'Advocacy is the active espousal of a legal cause.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. advocacy\n2. active espousal\n3. legal cause', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(7, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:53:00', '2016-05-28 14:53:00', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Case Method of Law Study', 'The case-study method requires that the student carefully examine individual cases to develop an understanding of legal processes and the relationship between judicial theories and practical legal problems. The student must have a precise understanding of the case\\''s material facts, holding, legal reasoning, authorities cited, and legal process utilized to benefit from this method of study. Merely understanding the gist of a case is insufficient.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. examine individual cases\n2. develop understanding of legal process\n3. understand relationship between judicial theory and practical legal\nproblems\n4. material facts\n5. holding\n6. legal reasoning\n7. authorities cited\n8. legal process\n9. merely understanding the gist of the case is insufficient', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(8, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:54:12', '2016-05-28 14:54:12', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Casebook', 'A casebook is the text which is used with the case method of law study. A casebook contains a collection of cases ordinarily organized to illustrate discrete legal principles.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. casebook\n2. text used for case method of law study\n3. collection of cases\n4. organized around discrete legal principles', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(9, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:55:11', '2016-05-28 14:55:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Outlines', 'A student may organize his or her thoughts regarding a collection of related legal principles and processes in an outline format to be used as a study aid. Commercial outlines are also available which provide an organized text summarizing legal principles.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. student\\''s organized thought\n2. legal principles and processes\n3. outline format\n4. study aid\n5. commercial outlines', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(10, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:56:11', '2016-05-28 14:56:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Bar Examination', 'A bar examination is one component of the requirements which must be successfully completed in order to become licensed to practice before courts of a particular state or jurisdiction.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. bar examination\n2. one of several components to complete in order to become a licensed\nattorney', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction to Legal Education', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(11, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:56:34', '2016-05-28 14:56:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Case Brief', 'A case brief is a generic term for a short, organized document created and utilized by the student or attorney, which summarizes key aspects of a case. A brief should contain parts of the case selected as important and organized for the purpose at hand, which may not necessarily be the haphazard order in which the parts may have been reported.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. case brief\n2. short, organized document\n3. summarizes key aspects of case', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(12, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:57:03', '2016-05-28 14:57:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Case briefs may utilize \\"FIRAC\\"', 'Generally speaking, a case brief usually contains the material facts of case, the issue presented to the court, the rule of law, the analysis, and the conclusion or resolution of the issue. A case brief may also include the case citation, procedural steps, and a summary of the dissent.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. facts\n2. issue\n3. rule of law\n4. analysis\n5. conclusion\n6. may also include citation, procedural steps, summary of dissent where present', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(13, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:57:37', '2016-05-28 14:57:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Material Fact', 'Material facts are those facts which have legal consequences. Summarizing material facts for a case brief does not require reciting all the details which can be learned, but rather selecting events that are relevant to the court\\''s decision.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. material fact\n2. fact with legal consequence\n3. summarize material facts for case brief\n4. select events relevant to decision', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(14, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:58:40', '2016-05-28 14:58:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Issue or question presented', 'The issue of a case is the question which the parties to litigation present to the court for decision.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. issue is a question\n2. presented by parties to litigation\n3. court resolves or decides the issue presented', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(15, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:59:03', '2016-05-28 14:59:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Elements of a Crime', 'In order to prevail in a criminal case, the prosecution is required to prove beyond a reasonable doubt the constituent parts of the crime which the defendant is accused. These parts are commonly referred to as the \\"elements of a crime\\". Under the Model Penal Code, the component parts of a crime include the actus reus, causation, mens rea, mitigating factors and defenses.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. prosecution must establish the constituent parts of a crime\n2. Model Penal Code components\n3. actus reus\n4. causation\n5. mens rea\n6. mitigating factors\n7. defenses', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(16, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 14:59:57', '2016-05-28 14:59:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rules applicable to the case', 'To resolve a case, rules of law are ordinarily applied to the unique facts of the issue before the court. Constitutional, statutory, case law, or administrative regulations are among the rules of law which a judge may rely upon to decide the case.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. rule of law\n2. apply to facts\n3. resolve dispute\n4. constitutional, statutory, case law, or administrative regulations', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(17, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:00:34', '2016-05-28 15:00:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Analysis (Case Briefs)', 'Judges apply legal principles to unique factual situations before the court and test the application by weighing potential legal consequences. The analysis of a court decision is the official explanation of how the judge responsible for the decision arrived at its result.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. applying legal principles to unique factual situations\n2. test application by weighing potential legal consequences\n3. official explanations for case result.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(18, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:00:56', '2016-05-28 15:00:56', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Holding of a case', 'The holding of a case answers the issue or question presented in the case. The case holding may be a single sentence and generally includes facts important to the rule of law applied in the case.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. holding of a case answers the issue\n2. may be a single sentence\n3. generally includes facts important to the rule of law applied to the case', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(19, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:01:14', '2016-05-28 15:01:14', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Authorities', 'Citations to constitutions, statutes, precedents, judicial decisions, rules, regulations, textbooks, articles, and the like made to support a legal argument before the court.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. citations\n2. constitutions\n3. statutes\n4. precedents\n5. judicial decisions,\n6. regulations\n7. textbooks\n8. articles\n9. to support a legal argument', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(20, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:01:35', '2016-05-28 15:01:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Case heading', 'Preceding each published court decision is a heading which includes: 1) names of the parties to the suit, 2) citation of the case including the volume and page number where the case can be found, 3) name of the court which decided the dispute, and 4) the date the decision was reached.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. heading precedes each published court decision\n2. citation, including volume and page number\n3. name of the court which decided the dispute\n4. date decision was reached', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(21, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:01:59', '2016-05-28 15:01:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Head Note', 'A head note summarizes all key points discussed and issues decided in a case. Head notes follow the heading of the case and precede the text of the judicial opinion.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. summarizes key points and issues of a case\n2. follows case heading\n3. precedes text of judicial opinion', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(22, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:02:17', '2016-05-28 15:02:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Procedure', 'The method of proceeding to enforce a legal right. Procedure should be distinguished from substantive law which gives or defines the right which one is attempting to enforce.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. method of proceeding to enforce a legal right\n2. distinguish from substantive law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Case Briefs', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(23, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:04:22', '2016-05-28 15:04:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Analysis', 'The process of examining the individual parts of a decision to either: 1) render one\\''s own decision or interpretation based on the law and facts presented, or 2) critically review another\\''s decision or interpretation based on then existing law and facts.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. process of examining individual parts\n2. render own decision or interpretation\n3. critically review another\\''s decision or interpretation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Skills', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(24, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:05:44', '2016-05-28 15:05:44', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Interpretation', 'Interpretation is the method of construing the language of either a statute, contract, or other written document to elicit its true, intended meaning.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. construing language\n2. statute or written document\n3. illicit true, intended meaning', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Skills', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(25, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:06:04', '2016-05-28 15:06:04', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Reasoning', 'Reasoning is the act of thinking logically.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. thinking logically', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Skills', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(26, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:43:15', '2016-05-28 15:43:15', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Analogy', 'An analogy is an inference that if two situations or principles are alike in some respects, then they must be alike in other respects as well.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. inference\n2. if similar in some respects, then similar in other respects', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Skills', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(27, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 15:58:50', '2016-05-28 15:58:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Syllogism', 'The word â€œsyllogismâ€ comes from the discipline of logic. Syllogism means the full logical form of a single argument and it consists of two premises and a conclusion for a total of three propositions. Each of the two premises contain a unique term which are related together in the conclusion.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. syllogism is a logic term\n2. three propositions\n3. two premises with unique terms brought together in conclusion', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Skills', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(28, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:03:58', '2016-05-28 16:03:58', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Research', 'The process of using resources to find the law as it has been delineated by courts, legislatures, and other governmental agencies, for the purpose of learning the law or answering a legal problem.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. using resources to find the law\n2. academic purpose\n3. solve a legal problem', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Skills', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(29, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:04:42', '2016-05-28 16:04:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law', 'Common law is a body of principles and rules of action which derive power solely from customary usage through history or from judicial decisions. Common law is distinct from statutory law.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. common law\n2. body of principles and rules\n3. power from customary usage throughout time\n4. power from judicial decisions\n5. distinct from statutory law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(30, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:05:12', '2016-05-28 16:05:12', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law Action', 'An action at common law is one which will lie without a governing statute.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. common law action\n2. no governing statute', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(31, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:05:47', '2016-05-28 16:05:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Forms of Action', '\\"Forms of action\\" were the procedural devices used at common law to give meaning to the theories of liability which the common law recognized. According to the type of relief sought, actions were strictly divided into discrete categories. Failure to properly analyze the cause of action and select the appropriate theory of liability or procedural form of action may have resulted in being thrown out of court all together.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. procedural devices at common law\n2. improper form of action may result in being thrown out of court', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(32, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:06:04', '2016-05-28 16:06:04', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Forms of Action compared to civil action', 'Modernly, under the Rules of Civil Procedure either at the state or federal level, there is only one form of action, the \\"civil action\\" for all theories of liability.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. Rules of Civil Procedure\n2. civil action', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(33, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:06:18', '2016-05-28 16:06:18', 1, NULL, NULL, 'English Common Law', 'English common law is the ancient, unwritten law of England.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. unwritten law of England', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(34, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:06:31', '2016-05-28 16:06:31', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Federal Common Law', 'Federal common law is law which is based on federal court decisions. Its application is limited by the Erie Doctrine.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. federal common law\n2. federal court decisions\n3. limited by the Erie Doctrine', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(35, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:07:00', '2016-05-28 16:07:00', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Erie Doctrine', 'The Erie Doctrine is a legal doctrine derived from a case by the same name which states that, except for cases governed by the federal constitution, U.S. treaties, or federal statutory law, federal courts must apply state substantive law and federal procedural law in cases decided by the federal courts.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. federal courts apply state substantive law\n2. federal courts apply federal procedural law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(36, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:07:24', '2016-05-28 16:07:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Equity', 'Equity is a form of justice administered according to precepts of fairness. Equity denotes a spirit of doing justice between parties according to what is fair under all circumstances in a particular case.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. form of justice\n2. fairness in a particular situation between individual parties', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(37, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:07:40', '2016-05-28 16:07:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Equity Contrasted with Common Law', 'Equity principles developed in England as a response to the perceived unfair harshness which common law rules rigidly imposed upon parties to an action.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. equity principles\n2. developed in England\n3. response to harshness of common law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(38, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:07:57', '2016-05-28 16:07:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Merger of Law and Equity', 'Modernly, federal courts and most state courts have merged the procedural aspects of law and equity under the term \\"civil suit.\\" Substantive concepts of equity and law still exist separately today.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. federal and most state courts\n2. merger of procedural aspects of law and equity\n3. separate substantive law and equity concepts', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law and Equity: Origins and Development', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(39, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:08:26', '2016-05-28 16:08:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Decisions', 'A judicial decision is a judgment, decree, or order pronounced by a court in settlement of a controversy submitted to it, providing an authoritative answer to the question presented.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. judgment, decree or order\n2. settlement of a controversy\n3. authoritative answer to question presented', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(40, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:08:38', '2016-05-28 16:08:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Actions', 'An action is a lawsuit which is filed in court.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. action\n2. lawsuit\n3. court', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(41, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:08:55', '2016-05-28 16:08:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Cause of Action', 'A cause of action is the circumstance or state of facts enabling a party to sustain an action and gives the right to seek a judicial remedy.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. circumstance or state of facts\n2. sustain an action\n3. seek judicial redress', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(42, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:09:15', '2016-05-28 16:09:15', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Remedy', 'Remedy refers to the means used to enforce a right or redress a legal injury.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. means to enforce right', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(43, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:16:38', '2016-05-28 16:16:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Justice', 'The term â€œjusticeâ€ is ordinarily used in one of two ways. First, â€œJusticeâ€ is the title given to judges in the higher levels of state and federal court. Second, â€œjusticeâ€ also refers to the proper administration of societal laws.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. two definitions for justice\n2. first, title for judge in higher state or federal court\n3. second, proper administration of societal laws', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(44, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:16:58', '2016-05-28 16:16:58', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Question of Fact', 'A question of fact is an issue involving the resolution of a factual dispute. Questions of fact are always within the province of the jury, unless the judge is acting as the trier of fact in place of a jury.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. issue involving resolution of a factual dispute\n2. jury question, unless judge substitutes for jury as trier of fact', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(45, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:17:40', '2016-05-28 16:17:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Question of Law', 'A question of law is an issue which entails the application or interpretation of a law and is always solely within the province of the judge.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. entails application or interpretation of law\n2. judge question', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(46, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:17:55', '2016-05-28 16:17:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Fiction', 'A legal fiction is a situation contrived by the law or a circumstance assumed by a court to support the resolution of legal question.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. situation contrived by law\n2. circumstance assumed by a court\n3. supports resolution of a legal question', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(47, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:18:27', '2016-05-28 16:18:27', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Conclusion of Law', 'Under the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, a judicial determination, without the assistance of a jury resolution, that particular facts have been established with such a degree of certainty that they may be deemed conclusions of law. The judge must state conclusions of law in a separate writing.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. Federal Rules of Civil Procedure\n2. judicial determination\n3. facts established a degree of certainty\n4. must be in separate writing', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(48, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:18:43', '2016-05-28 16:18:43', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Ratio Decidendi', 'â€œRatio Decidendiâ€ is a Latin term meaning the point in a case which determines the outcome in judgment.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. point in case which determines outcome', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(49, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:18:59', '2016-05-28 16:18:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Role of Judge and Jury', 'The general rule is that the judge determines questions of law and the jury determines question of fact in litigation. Where there is no jury, the judge decides both questions of law and questions of fact.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. judge decides questions of law\n2. jury decides questions of fact\n3. if no jury, judge decides both questions of law and of fact', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(50, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:19:17', '2016-05-28 16:19:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Precedent', 'A precedent case is a case which has been decided earlier in time to a later case and both cases turn on the same or substantially similar legal issues and/or facts.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. case decided earlier in time and turned on same or similar issues of fact and/or law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(51, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:19:40', '2016-05-28 16:19:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Obiter Dictum or Dictum', 'Dictum is language or concept in a judge\\''s opinion which is not necessary to the resolution of the issues in the case or goes beyond the scope of the facts or issues in the case. Dictum is not binding in subsequent cases under the precedence doctrine.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. language or concept which is unnecessary to resolution of case\n2. language or concept which goes beyond the facts or issues of the case\n3. not binding on subsequent judicial opinions', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(52, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:20:03', '2016-05-28 16:20:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Stare Decisis', 'A Latin term which means to adhere to previously decided cases or that precedent cases should be followed. This doctrine is limited to actual determinations by the court regarding litigated matters and necessarily decided questions. Dictum does not come under the Doctrine of Stare Decisis.\r\nKey Words or Phrases:\r\n1. adherence to previously decided cases\r\n2. precedents should be followed\r\n3. limited to actual, necessary judicial determinations\r\n4. dictum does not come under stare decisis ', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(53, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:20:44', '2016-05-28 16:20:44', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Prospective Overruling', 'A judicial decision prospectively overrules when its decision will be applied only to future cases.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. judicial overruling\n2. applied only to future cases', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(54, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:20:59', '2016-05-28 16:20:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Retroactive Effect of Judicial Decisions', 'A decision is said to have retroactive effect where it is intended to act on past rights, obligations or duties.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. intended to act on past rights, obligations or duties', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Judicial Process and Style', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(55, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:21:26', '2016-05-28 16:21:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Civil Procedure', 'Civil procedure is the body of law concerned with procedural aspects of civil litigation. At the federal level, these rules of procedure are called the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. body of law concerned with procedure in civil litigation\n2. Federal Rules of Civil Procedure', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Civil Procedure', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(56, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:21:46', '2016-05-28 16:21:46', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Diversity Jurisdiction of Federal Courts', 'Article III, Section 2 of the United States Constitution states that federal court jurisdiction extends to all cases and controversies between citizens of different states. In order for the federal court to have jurisdiction, the amount in controversy requirement must also be satisfied.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. Article III, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution\n2. federal court jurisdiction\n3. case and controversy between citizens of different states\n4. amount in controversy requirement', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Civil Procedure', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(57, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:22:04', '2016-05-28 16:22:04', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Federal Question Jurisdiction', 'Federal courts are also authorized under Article III, Section 2 of the United States Constitution to hear cases arising under the Constitution of the United States, congressional acts, or treaties.\r\nKey Words or Phrases:\r\n1. Article III, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution\r\n2. federal court jurisdiction\r\n3. cases "arising under"\r\n4. U.S. Constitution\r\n5. Congressional acts\r\n6. treaties', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Civil Procedure', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(58, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:22:51', '2016-05-28 16:22:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Writ of Certiorari', 'An order prepared by an appellate court, when that court may exercise discretion regarding whether or not to hear an appeal from a lower court, is called a â€œWrit of Certiorari.â€ Specifically regarding the U.S. Supreme Court, a review by the Writ of Certiorari may prevail only when there are special and important reasons to hear the case.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. order prepared by appellate court\n2. when appellate court has discretion to hear appeal from lower court\n3. on writ of certiorari, U.S. Supreme Court hears where special and important reasons exist', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Civil Procedure', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(59, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:23:17', '2016-05-28 16:23:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Alternative Dispute Process', 'The term â€œalternative dispute processâ€ or â€œalternative dispute resolution,â€ refers to a method of settling legal disputes other than litigation. Common examples of alternative dispute processes include arbitration and mediation.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. alternative dispute process\n2. alternative dispute resolution\n3. method of settling legal dispute other than litigation\n4. arbitration\n5. mediation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(60, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:23:36', '2016-05-28 16:23:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Arbitration', 'Arbitration is a form of alternative dispute resolution which requires that a neutral third party, called an arbitrator, render a decision after hearing both parties to a dispute present their respective sides of the dispute. Arbitration can be either voluntary or involuntary.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. form of alternative dispute resolution\n2. arbitrator renders decision after hearing', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(61, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:24:06', '2016-05-28 16:24:06', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mediation', 'Mediation is also a form of alternative dispute resolution, which requires that a neutral third party, called a mediator, assist both parties to a dispute agree to a mutually acceptable resolution. Mediation differs from arbitration in that the mediator has no power to render a decision; an arbitrator has the power to render a decision resolving the dispute.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. form of alternative dispute resolution\n2. mediator assists both parties to resolve their dispute by agreement\n3. mediator has no power to render a decision', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Alternative Dispute Resolution', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(62, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:24:26', '2016-05-28 16:24:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legislature', 'The legislature is one of the three branches of government which exist at both the state and federal levels. Each body of legislators is responsible for promulgating state and federal statutory law, respectively.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. federal legislature responsible for promulgating federal statute\n2. state legislature responsible for promulgating state statute', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory & Administrative Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(63, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:24:41', '2016-05-28 16:24:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Statute', 'A statute is merely the formal, written enactment of a legislative body which can be either the federal, state or local level of government.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. formal, written enactment\n2. legislative body\n3. federal, state or local level of government', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory & Administrative Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(64, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:25:05', '2016-05-28 16:25:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Uniform Commercial Code', 'The Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) governs a variety of commercial transactions. The UCC was intended to be adopted in some form by the individual states, thereby creating a degree of similarity between different state laws regarding commercial transactions. All states have adopted the UCC in some form.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. UCC\n2. governs commercial transactions\n3. intended to create uniformity among differing state commercial laws\n4. all states have adopted in some form', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory & Administrative Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(65, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:25:34', '2016-05-28 16:25:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Administrative Agencies', 'An administrative agency is a governmental agency organized under constitutional or statutory authority, which is responsible for administering and supervising an area of public interest designated in the law which created it. An administrative agency may have authority to promulgate regulations, or make administrative determinations which potentially have the force and effect of law.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. governmental agency\n2. constitutional or statutory\n3. administers and supervises designated area of public interest\n4. may promulgate regulations with force and effect of law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory & Administrative Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(66, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:25:46', '2016-05-28 16:25:46', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Administrative law', 'A regulation or order passed by an administrative agency having the force and effect of law.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. regulation or order\n2. administrative agency\n3. force and effect of law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory & Administrative Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(67, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:26:10', '2016-05-28 16:26:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Canons of Construction', 'Canons of construction are a body of rules or maxims which indicate the appropriate meaning or interpretation of statutes or written instruments.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. body of rules or maxims\n2. indicate appropriate meaning or interpretation\n3. statutes or written instruments', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interpretation of Statutes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(68, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:26:23', '2016-05-28 16:26:23', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Plain Meaning Rule', 'The â€œplain meaning ruleâ€ is a rule of construction which states that words should be interpreted using their ordinary or plain meaning.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. rule of construction\n2. interpret words using ordinary meaning', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interpretation of Statutes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(69, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:26:35', '2016-05-28 16:26:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Statutes in Pari Materia', 'Two or more statutes which must be construed together because they relate to the same subject are said to be in pari materia.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. construe two or more statutes together\n2. relate to same subject matter', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interpretation of Statutes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(70, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:26:58', '2016-05-28 16:26:58', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legislative History', 'The process or result of research in the documentary records of the legislature as they relate to the drafting, analysis and passage of law or rejection of a proposed law is called the â€œlegislative history.â€\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. process or result of research\n2. documentary records of the legislature\n3. relating to drafting, analysis and passage or defeat of statute', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interpretation of Statutes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(71, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:27:17', '2016-05-28 16:27:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legislative Intent', 'After analyzing the legislative history of a particular statute, a court attempts to determine the intent of the legislature for passing the statute in question, so that the judge may apply the statute to the case at hand as intended by the legislators.\nKey Words or Phrases:\n1. intent determined from legislative history\n2. intent used by court to further intent of the legislators in passing the statute', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Interpretation of Statutes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, NULL),
(72, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:28:25', '2016-05-28 16:28:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Common Law', 'The common law governs contracts not governed by the UCC.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. contract in which the subject matter is not the sale of goods', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Governing Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(73, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:32:18', '2016-05-28 16:32:18', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Uniform Commercial Code', 'The Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) governs contracts for the sale of goods.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. contract for sale of goods', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Governing Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(74, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:32:34', '2016-05-28 16:32:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Goods', 'Goods are tangible chattels which are moveable and identifiable to the contract at the time of formation.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. tangible chattel\n2. moveable\n3. identified in the contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Governing Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(75, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:40:34', '2016-05-28 16:40:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Contract for Both Goods and Services', 'Usually the court will apply the â€œpredominant factor testâ€ to see if the contractâ€™s primary purpose is sale of goods or provision of services and then apply the appropriate law. However, the court may apply the UCC to the goods portion of the contract, and the common law to the remaining terms.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. predominate factor test is used to assess the primary purpose of the contract\n2. or divide the contract and apply the UCC to the portion dealing with the sale of goods and common law to the remainder', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Governing Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL);
INSERT INTO `records_lawcourse` (`id`, `uid`, `created`, `updated`, `status`, `lat`, `lng`, `title`, `description`, `details`, `path`, `deleted`, `users_info_id`, `location_id`, `admin_approved`, `i1`, `i2`, `i3`, `i4`, `d1`, `d2`, `d3`, `d4`, `vc1`, `vc2`, `vc3`, `vc4`, `t1`, `t2`, `t3`, `t4`, `parent_id`, `reference_id`, `expiry_dt`) VALUES
(76, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:40:55', '2016-05-28 16:40:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Merchant', 'Under the UCC, a merchant is one who deals regularly in the kind of goods involved in the contract, or one who holds himself out as having special knowledge or skill about the practices or goods involved in the contract. Merchants owe a duty to observe reasonable commercial standards of fair dealing.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Governing Law', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(77, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:41:16', '2016-05-28 16:41:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Contract', 'A contract is an agreement between two or more parties which the law will enforce.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. agreement\n2. two or more parties\n3. enforceable by law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Formation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(78, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:41:30', '2016-05-28 16:41:30', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Elements of a Contract', 'The necessary elements of a contract are offer, acceptance, and consideration.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. offer\n2. acceptance\n3. consideration', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Formation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(79, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:41:50', '2016-05-28 16:41:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mutual Assent', 'Mutual assent relates to the requirement that the parties agree to enter into a contractual relationship, including terms and conditions. It is usually proved by showing that one party made a valid offer and the other party made a valid acceptance.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. agreement to enter contractual relationship', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Formation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(80, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:42:10', '2016-05-28 16:42:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Meeting of the Minds', 'The historic rule holds that mutual assent exists if there was a â€œmeeting of the mindsâ€ between the parties, meaning that the parties subjectively intended to enter into a legally binding contract and agreed to the terms and conditions of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mutual assent exists where there was a meeting of the minds\n2. subjective intent of parties to enter a contract\n3. agreement as to terms and conditions', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Formation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(81, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:42:31', '2016-05-28 16:42:31', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Objective Theory of Contracts', 'The modern rule holds that mutual assent exists if a reasonable person would objectively have understood the outward actions and statements of the other party to indicate an intent to enter into a legally binding contract and agreement to terms and conditions of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mutual assent exists where there were outward manifestations demonstrating intent to contract.\n2. objective interpretation of partiesâ€™ actions and statements', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Formation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(82, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:42:57', '2016-05-28 16:42:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Formation', 'Under the UCC, a contract for sale of goods may be made in any manner sufficient to show agreement, including conduct by both parties which recognizes the existence of such contract. Additionally, under the UCC, a contract for sale may be found even though the moment of its making is undetermined.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. any manner which shows agreement or contract\n2. moment of formation may be undetermined', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Formation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(83, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 16:43:20', '2016-05-28 16:43:20', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'An offer is a manifestation of present contractual intent which includes certain and definite terms; is communicated to the offeree; proposes a bargain in which the offerorâ€™s act, forbearance to act, or promise is exchanged for the offereeâ€™s act, forbearance to act, or return promise; and creates a power of acceptance in the offeree.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. manifestation\n2. present contractual intent\n3. certain and definite terms\n4. communicated to offeree\n5. proposal for a bargain: act, forbearance to act, or promise exchanged\n6. offeree has power of acceptance', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(84, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:00:52', '2016-05-28 17:00:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Advertisement', 'Under the majority rule, an advertisement is not an offer but is merely an invitation for offers. Under the minority rule, if an advertisement includes definite and certain terms, it may be an offer.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. usually just an invitation for offers', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(85, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:01:15', '2016-05-28 17:01:15', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Revocation', 'Revocation results from the canceling, annulling, or otherwise voiding of an offer. An offer may freely be revoked by the offeror unless 1) the offer was for a unilateral contract and the offeree has already begun performance, 2) the offer was a firm offer, in which case it terminates at the end of the time stated without the need for further action by any party, or 3) the offeree detrimentally relied on the offer.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. making void an offer\n2. offer is revocable by offeror\n3. exceptions:\n  a. unilateral contract with performance begun;\n  b. firm offer;\n  c. detrimental reliance by offeree', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(86, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:01:31', '2016-05-28 17:01:31', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Revocation Effective upon Receipt by Offeree', 'A revocation is effective upon receipt by the offeree. A minority view holds that the revocation becomes effective when sent by the offeror.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. majority: revocation effective upon receipt\n2. minority: revocation effective when sent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(87, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:01:45', '2016-05-28 17:01:45', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Counteroffer', 'A counteroffer is an offer by the original offeree regarding the same transaction but containing terms that differ from those proposed in the original offer made by the offeror.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. offer by original offeree\n2. regarding same transaction\n3. containing different terms', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(88, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:02:03', '2016-05-28 17:02:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Counteroffer as an Implied Rejection', 'A counteroffer is an implied rejection of the original offer. It is, in effect, a new offer available for acceptance.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. counteroffer is implied rejection\n2. counteroffer is a new offer', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Offer', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(89, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:02:36', '2016-05-28 17:02:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'An acceptance is an unequivocal assent to the terms of an offer.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unequivocal assent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(90, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:03:44', '2016-05-28 17:03:44', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mirror Image Rule', 'Under the common law Mirror Image Rule, an acceptance must match the terms of the offer. If the acceptance contains additional or different terms, it is a counter offer rather than an acceptance. However, modernly the UCC modifies this rule to allow an acceptance to differ from the offer as to minor terms.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. acceptance must match offer', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(91, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:04:05', '2016-05-28 17:04:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Acceptance', 'Under the UCC, â€œa definite and seasonable expression of acceptance or a written confirmation which is sent within a reasonable time operates as an acceptance even though it states terms additional to or different from those offered or agreed upon, unless acceptance is expressly made conditional on assent to the additional or different terms.â€\r\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\r\n1. acceptance can be made by:\r\na. definite and seasonable expression of acceptance, or\r\nb. written confirmation sent within reasonable time\r\n2. additional or different terms do not negate acceptance unless acceptance is expressly conditional on assent to such terms', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(92, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:05:16', '2016-05-28 17:05:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Methods of Acceptance', 'â€œThe offeror is the master of his offer.â€ If the offeror states a required mode of acceptance, the offeree must accept using that mode. If the offeror does not state a required mode of acceptance, then under the older common law rule, the acceptance must be made by the same mode as the offer, and under modern common law, the acceptance must be made by the same mode as the offer or by a reasonable mode.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. the offeror can specify a mode of communication for acceptance\n2. if the offeror does not specify:\na. under the old common law: same mode as offer\nb. under modern common law: same mode as offer or a reasonable mode', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(93, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:05:36', '2016-05-28 17:05:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mailbox Rule', 'Under the Mailbox Rule, established in the case of Adams v. Lindsell, an acceptance of an offer for a bilateral contract, dispatched by an authorized mode of communication, is effective when mailed.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. acceptance effective when mailed', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(94, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:06:23', '2016-05-28 17:06:23', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Methods of Acceptance', 'Under the UCC, unless otherwise clearly indicated, acceptance may be made in any reasonable way, including a promise to ship or prompt shipment. Even a shipment of non conforming goods constitutes acceptance unless the seller notifies the buyer that the non-conforming goods are offered only as an accommodation to the buyer.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. acceptance can be made:\n  a. in any manner and by any reasonable mode unless the offer or circumstances dictate otherwise,\n  b. by a promise to ship\n  c. by prompt shipment\n2. shipment of non-conforming goods constitutes acceptance unless the seller provides notice that the shipment is an accommodation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(95, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:06:42', '2016-05-28 17:06:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Acceptance by Conduct', 'Under the UCC, conduct by both parties which demonstrates the existence of a contract is sufficient to establish a contract, even though the writings of the parties do not otherwise establish a contract. In such a case the terms of the contract consist of those terms on which the writings of the parties agree, plus other terms provided by the UCC.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. both parties act in a way which demonstrates recognition of a contract\n2. contract consists of agreed terms plus additional or different terms according to the UCC', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(96, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:06:55', '2016-05-28 17:06:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rejection', 'A rejection is a manifestation by the offeree that he or she does not intend to accept the offer nor to give it further consideration.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. manifestation by the offeree\n2. does not intend to accept the offer', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(97, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:07:22', '2016-05-28 17:07:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rejection Effective when Received', 'A rejection becomes effective upon receipt by the offeror.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. rejection effective upon receipt by offeror', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Acceptance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(98, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 17:07:47', '2016-05-28 17:07:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Consideration is that which is bargained for and given in exchange for a promise. It may be an act, a forbearance to act, or a return promise on the part of the promisee, but it must include a legal detriment to both parties in order to be valid.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. that which is bargained for and given in exchange\n2. an act, a forbearance to act, or a return promise', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(99, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:16:11', '2016-05-28 21:16:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legal Detriment', 'A legal detriment is a promise to do something that one is not legally obligated to do, or to refrain from doing something that one is legally privileged to do.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. promise to do something that one is not legally obligated to do, or\n2. promise to refrain from doing something that one is legally privileged to do', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(100, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:17:11', '2016-05-28 21:17:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Sufficiency of Consideration', 'Generally, courts do not require that the consideration benefit the promisee, nor that it be of any substantial value, as long as there is some legal detriment to the promisor so that the consideration serves as an inducement for the return promise of the promisee.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. consideration need not benefit offeree or be of substantial value\n2. consideration must include legal detriment to serve as inducement for promise', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(101, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:17:26', '2016-05-28 21:17:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Valuable Consideration', 'Valuable consideration is consideration that is legally valid, meaning that confers a benefit to the promisor in exchange for his detriment.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. legally valid consideration\n2. benefit in exchange for detriment', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(102, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:17:41', '2016-05-28 21:17:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Illusory Promise', 'An illusory promise is an expression , resembles promissory terms, but in actuality imposes no obligation upon the party making it so that the element of legal detriment is lacking.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. expression resembles promissory terms\n2. terms actually impose no obligation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(103, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:18:06', '2016-05-28 21:18:06', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Promissory Estoppel', 'The Doctrine of Promissory Estoppel provides a substitute for the element of consideration when there has been a foreseeable and detrimental reliance by the promisee upon the gratuitous promise made by the promisor.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. substitute for consideration\n2. foreseeable, detrimental reliance upon a gratuitous promise', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(104, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:18:36', '2016-05-28 21:18:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Moral Obligation Rule', 'Under the Moral Obligation Rule, consideration may be found if the promisor has received something of value from the promisee under such circumstances as to create a moral obligation for the promisor to pay for what he or she has received, and if the promisor has later promised to pay. The rule most often applies in situations involving promises to pay for previously provided gratuitous services, promises to pay debts barred by the statute of limitations, or promises to pay debts discharged in bankruptcy. The promise to pay can be implied by a mere acknowledgment of a debt or by part payment of the debt.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. moral obligation to pay for benefit received\n2. combined with:\na. a later promise to pay, or\nb. an acknowledgment of the debt, or\nc. part payment of the debt', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consideration', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(105, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:19:39', '2016-05-28 21:19:39', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Terms', 'Under the common law, a contract must include the following terms: quantity, time for performance, identity of parties, price, and subject matter. Missing terms may result in a failure to contract for indefiniteness of terms. Under the UCC, a contract must include the parties and the quantity, but â€œgap fillersâ€ may be used to supply other missing terms if there is a reasonably certain basis for determining the missing term.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. common law:\nQTIPS: quantity; time; identity of parties; price; and subject matter\n2. UCC:\nParties; quantity; and gap fillers', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(106, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:20:14', '2016-05-28 21:20:14', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Absence of Specified Place for Delivery', 'Under the UCC, unless otherwise agreed, delivery is at the seller\\''s place of business or at his residence if he has no place of business. However, if both parties know, at the time the contract is formed, that the goods are in some other place, that place is the place for their delivery. An exception is made for documents of title, which may be delivered through customary banking channels.\r\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\r\n1. if the contract does not state delivery terms:\r\na. delivery of goods at sellerâ€™s business location or, if none, at sellerâ€™s residence\r\nb. exception: if both parties know goods are elsewhere at the time of contract,\r\nthat location is the place of delivery\r\nc. place of delivery for title documents is usual banking channels', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(107, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:21:52', '2016-05-28 21:21:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Open Time for Payment', 'Under the UCC, unless otherwise agreed, payment is due at the time and place at which the buyer is to receive the goods or documents of title. However, unless the contract provides otherwise, the buyer may inspect the goods after their arrival and prior to payment.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. if contract does not state time for payment:\na. payment is due upon receipt of goods or title\nb. buyer may inspect goods prior to paying', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(108, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:22:12', '2016-05-28 21:22:12', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Risk of Loss', 'Generally the risk of loss of goods during shipment is placed upon the party who was in the best position to have insured against risk of loss. If the seller is a merchant, then the seller bears the risk of loss until the buyer receives the goods; if the seller is not a merchant, then the buyer assumes the risk of loss once the goods are tendered for delivery.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. risk of loss is generally on party in best position to insure\n2. merchant bears risk of loss until buyer receives goods\n3. non-merchant bears risk of loss until tender for delivery occurs', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(109, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:22:35', '2016-05-28 21:22:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'F.O.B.', 'The abbreviation â€œF.O.B.â€ stands for â€œfree on board,â€ and means that the buyer pays shipping costs and once the seller puts the goods into the carrierâ€™s possession for shipping, the buyer bears the risk of loss.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. buyer pays shipping\n2. buyer bears risk of loss once carrier takes possession', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(110, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:22:55', '2016-05-28 21:22:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'F.O.B. Destination', 'â€œF.O.B. Destinationâ€ means that the seller pays the shipping costs to a specified destination and bears the risk of loss to such destination. Reasonable notice that the goods have arrived at the destination and are available for the buyer to take delivery is required to relieve the seller of his risk of loss.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. seller pays shipping\n2. seller bears risk of loss to destination', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(111, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:23:25', '2016-05-28 21:23:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'F.A.S.', 'The abbreviation â€œF.A.S.â€ stands for â€œfree alongsideâ€ and means the buyer pays shipping costs and assumes the risk of loss once the seller places goods alongside a vessel for shipping.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. buyer pays shipping\n2. buyer bears risk of loss once goods are placed alongside vessel by seller', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(112, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:23:44', '2016-05-28 21:23:44', 1, NULL, NULL, 'C.I.F.', 'The abbreviation â€œC.I.F.â€ stands for â€œcost, insurance, freight,â€ and means the seller pays the cost of delivering goods to the carrier for shipment, as well as insurance and freight costs to the destination, but the buyer bears the risk of loss during transit.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. seller pays shipping costs, insurance, and freight\n2. buyer bears risk of loss during transit.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(113, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:24:51', '2016-05-28 21:24:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'No arrival no sale', 'â€œNo arrival no saleâ€ means that the seller has a duty to ship goods and bears the risk of loss during shipment. If the goods arrive damaged or late, through no fault of the sellerâ€™s, then the buyer has the option either to void the contract or to accept the goods at a discount.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. seller has duty to ship goods\n2. seller bears risk of loss during transit\n3. seller is exempted for liability for non-delivery so long as seller did not cause the non-delivery', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(114, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:25:11', '2016-05-28 21:25:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Shipment under reservation', 'â€œShipment under Reservationâ€ means that the seller ships the goods, but consigns them to himself at the destination so that he retains control of the goods in transit and until the buyer pays for them. The buyer will not receive the goods until payment has been made.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. seller consigns goods to himself, thus retaining control\n2. buyer receives right to receipt of goods only after payment', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(115, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:25:24', '2016-05-28 21:25:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Exculpatory Clause', 'An exculpatory clause is a provision in a contract that is intended to remove liability from one or more of the contracting parties that may result from certain acts or events.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. provision in a contract\n2. removes liability', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(116, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:25:47', '2016-05-28 21:25:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Privity of Contract', 'Privity of contract is the relationship that exists between the parties to an agreement, allowing them to sue each other to enforce the agreement, but preventing a third party from doing so.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. relationship between parties to an agreement\n2. confers standing to sue', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Terms of a contract', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(117, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:26:58', '2016-05-28 21:26:58', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'A â€œbattle of the formsâ€ may occur when parties use standardized forms to make offers and acceptances. Such forms contain fixed contractual language (boilerplate) which often conflicts with the terms included in the other partyâ€™s forms. Thus, although a contract may be formed through the exchange of such forms, the parties may disagree as to which terms govern the contract.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(118, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:27:46', '2016-05-28 21:27:46', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Additional or Different Terms in Acceptance or Confirmation by Non-merchants', 'Under the UCC, if additional or different terms are included in an acceptance for a contract between non-merchants, these terms are merely a proposal unless acceptance is expressly conditional on assent to the additional or different terms.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. non-merchants\n2. additional or different terms are a proposal only, unless acceptance is expressly conditioned on assent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(119, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:29:17', '2016-05-28 21:29:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Additional Terms in Acceptance or Confirmation by Merchants', 'Under the UCC, additional terms in an acceptance for a contract between merchants become part of the contract unless the offer expressly limits acceptance to the terms of the offer, the additional terms constitute a material alteration, or notification of objection to the additional terms has already been given or is given within a reasonable time after notice of them is received.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. contract between merchants\n2. acceptance includes additional terms unless:\na. the offer expressly limits acceptance to the terms of the offer, or\nb. additional terms constitute a material alteration, or\nc. notification of objection is already made or made within a reasonable time', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(120, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:31:33', '2016-05-28 21:31:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Different Terms in Acceptance or Confirmation by Merchants', 'Under the UCC, different terms in an acceptance for a contract between merchants do not generally become part of the contract even if they do not constitute a material alteration. There are different interpretations of the UCC and how such different terms are handled. The commonly applied rules are the Knockout Rule, the First Shot Rule, and the Last Shot Rule. Additionally, a proposed new rule is the Best Shot Rule; however, this rule has not yet been adopted by any jurisdiction.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. merchants\n2. different terms subject to various jurisdictional rules', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(121, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:33:08', '2016-05-28 21:33:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Knockout Rule', 'Under the Knockout Rule, different terms in an offer and acceptance are â€œknocked outâ€ of the contract, and the contract consists of those terms upon which the parties agree, with UCC gapfillers used to supply missing terms. Proponents of this rule favor it because they view the UCC gapfillers as more â€œfairâ€ where terms are different. Opponents of this rule argue that it encourages parties to include one-sided language in their contracts because the worst that will happen is that the one-sided terms could be knocked out and replaced with UCC gapfillers.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. all conflicting terms in both offer and acceptance are out\n2. UCC gapfillers are used for missing terms', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(122, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:33:34', '2016-05-28 21:33:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'First Shot Rule', 'Under the First Shot Rule, terms in an acceptance which are different from those in an offer are out, meaning that the contract consists of the terms of the offer. Proponents of this rule favor it because it supports the doctrine that the â€œofferor is master of his offer.â€ Opponents argue that this rule does nothing to discourage inclusion of one-sided terms in boilerplate contract language.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. different terms in acceptance are out; terms in offer are in', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(123, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:40:38', '2016-05-28 21:40:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Last Shot Rule', 'Under the Last Shot Rule, different terms are treated the same as additional terms. That is, different terms are treated as a proposal (i.e., counteroffer) and are deemed accepted and therefore binding, if followed by performance. Proponents of this rule favor it because it provides a simple rule for interpretation that, rather than favoring one partyâ€™s form over the others, aims toward finding a contract that consists of the terms upon which the parties appear to agree, allowing for both express terms and conduct to govern the agreement. Opponents argue that this rule favors whoever sends the last writing, because that partyâ€™s different terms will be included unless the recipient is careful to make a clear and timely objection.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. different terms in acceptance are in unless:\na. the offer expressly limits acceptance to the terms of the offer,\nb. additional terms constitute a material alteration, or\nc. notification of objection is already made or made within a reasonable time', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(124, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:41:12', '2016-05-28 21:41:12', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Best Shot Rule', 'Although not adopted by any jurisdiction, the proposed Best Shot Rule would determine which partyâ€™s forms include standard terms which are the most fair overall, and adopts those terms entirely. Proponents of this rule favor it because they believe it will encourage drafters of contracts to use terms that are more fair to all parties, rather than adopting one-sided boilerplate language. Opponents argue that an offeror should be free to propose a contract which appeals to him.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. different terms from the party whose forms are most fair overall are in', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Battle of the forms', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(125, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:45:25', '2016-05-28 21:45:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Firm Offer', 'Under the common law, a firm offer is an offer which is irrevocable because an option has been paid for by one of the parties. Under the UCC, an option need not be paid for if the firm offer was made by a merchant who signed it in writing giving assurance that the offer will remain open for a certain or reasonable length of time not to exceed three months.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. common law: offer is irrevocable if one party has paid for an option\n2. UCC: offer is irrevocable either because:\na. one party has paid for an option, or\nb. a merchant signed an offer which states it would remain open', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Irrevocable Offers', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(126, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:45:37', '2016-05-28 21:45:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Option', 'An option is a purchased right to perform or to require performance of the terms of a contract within a specified length of time.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. purchased\n2. right to perform or require performance\n3. specified length of time', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Irrevocable Offers', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(127, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:47:01', '2016-05-28 21:47:01', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Option Contract', 'An option contract is a contract which includes an option, that is, an agreement between parties which is supported by consideration and which involves a promise to hold an offer open for a specified period of time.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. agreement includes an option\n2. promise to hold offer open for a specified period of time.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Irrevocable Offers', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(128, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:47:35', '2016-05-28 21:47:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Caldwell v. Cline', 'Under Caldwell v. Cline, if an offer states that it will be open for a certain number of days, the first day is the day the offeree receives the offer.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. offer open for specified number of days\n2. first day is the day the offeree receives the offer', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Irrevocable Offers', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(129, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 21:47:51', '2016-05-28 21:47:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mailbox Rule and Acceptance of Options', 'The Mailbox Rule does not apply to acceptance of an option. The acceptance (exercising the option) is valid when received.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. Acceptance of option is valid when received', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Irrevocable Offers', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(130, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 22:04:51', '2016-05-28 22:04:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The Corpus Delicti', 'The corpus delicti is the body of the crime, meaning the prima facie case or elements of the crime. Generally, the term embodies both the obvious evidence of a crime and the logical conclusion based upon that evidence that the elements of a crime have been committed, for example, a dead body with a knife sticking out and the logical conclusion that a homicide has been committed.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(131, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-28 22:05:03', '2016-05-28 22:05:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Actus Reus', 'Actus reus refers to the overt act.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(132, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:39:47', '2016-05-29 00:39:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Malum In Se', 'Malum in se refers to a wrong in itself, in other words, something naturally evil.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(133, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:40:08', '2016-05-29 00:40:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Malum Prohibitum', 'Malum prohibitum refers to something made wrong by legislation.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(134, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:45:42', '2016-05-29 00:45:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Felony', 'A felony, in most jurisdictions, is a crime that is punishable by death or by a sentence of more than one year even though the sentence actually imposed is one year or less. However, in some states, a crime is a felony if the sentence is to be served in a state prison, as opposed to a county or city jail.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. crime punishable by death or sentence of more than one year, or\n2. sentence to be served in state prison', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(135, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:45:56', '2016-05-29 00:45:56', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Misdemeanor', 'A misdemeanor is any crime that is not felony.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. any crime that is not a felony', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(136, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:46:23', '2016-05-29 00:46:23', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Merger Rule', 'Under the Merger Doctrine, when all the elements of one crime are included within the elements of another crime, the lesser crime merges with the greater and a defendant cannot be convicted of both crimes. For example, larceny merges with robbery and battery merges with murder.\nAdditionally, the Merger Rule applies to solicitation and attempt, to prevent a person from being convicted of either of these and of the completed target crime.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(137, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:47:01', '2016-05-29 00:47:01', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mens Rea', 'Mens rea refers to a guilty mind or wrongful intent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(138, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:47:24', '2016-05-29 00:47:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Concurrence', 'Concurrence refers to the requirement that the actus reus and mens rea exist at the same time.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(139, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:47:57', '2016-05-29 00:47:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'General Intent', 'Under common law, general intent refers to the purposeful commission of a prohibited act where the performance of the act is sufficient to establish intent to commit the crime because intent is inferred from the fact that the act was done. Examples of general intent crimes are battery and rape.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. purposeful commission of prohibited act', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(140, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:48:32', '2016-05-29 00:48:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Specific Intent', 'Specific intent refers to the purposeful commission of a prohibited act with the aim of producing a particular result. Examples of specific intent crimes are burglary and larceny: for burglary, the specific intent to commit a felony within the dwelling house of another is required to constitute the crime (under common law); for larceny, the specific intent to permanently deprive the owner is required.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n3. purposeful commission of prohibited act\n4. goal to produce a particular result', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(141, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:48:59', '2016-05-29 00:48:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Transferred Intent Doctrine', 'The Transferred Intent Doctrine is applicable when a defendant, while in the process of committing a crime against one person, unintentionally commits the crime against a different person or commits a different crime. In such a case, the defendantâ€™s wrongful intent is transferred to include the unintended victim or crime. The Transferred Intent Doctrine applies only to general intent crimes.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n2. defendant performs a volitional act which constitutes a crime\n3. a. result is harm to a different victim than intended, or\nb. result is a different crime than intended', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(142, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:49:21', '2016-05-29 00:49:21', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Intent under the Model Penal Code', 'Under the MPC, the distinction between general and specific intent has been abandoned, and a person is generally guilty of an offense only if he acted purposefully, knowingly, recklessly or negligently, as the law for a particular crime may require, with respect to each material element of the offense.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. purposefully\n2. knowingly\n3. recklessly\n4. negligently', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(143, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:49:41', '2016-05-29 00:49:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Purposefully', 'Under the MPC, â€œpurposefullyâ€ means that the defendant acted with the conscious object to do the act or to cause the result of his act, or that the defendant acted while aware or hopeful that the circumstances which led to harm existed.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(144, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:49:57', '2016-05-29 00:49:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Knowingly', 'Under the MPC, â€œknowinglyâ€ means that the defendant acted with conscious awareness or substantial certainty that his act would produce its result or that the circumstances which led to harm existed.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(145, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:51:39', '2016-05-29 00:51:39', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Recklessly', 'Under the MPC, â€œrecklesslyâ€ means that the defendant acted with conscious disregard of a substantial and unjustifiable risk that his act would result in a crime, such that his disregard involved a gross deviation from the standard of conduct that a law-abiding person would observe in the actor\\''s situation.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(146, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:52:05', '2016-05-29 00:52:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Negligently', 'Under the MPC, â€œnegligentlyâ€ means that the defendant should have been aware of a substantial and unjustifiable risk that a crime would result from his act. The risk must be of such a nature and degree that the actor\\''s failure to perceive it, considering the nature and purpose of his conduct and the circumstances known to him, involves a gross deviation from the standard of care that a reasonable person would observe in the actor\\''s situation.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(147, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:52:43', '2016-05-29 00:52:43', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Intent for Inchoate Crimes', 'Even if the target crime is a general intent crime, the inchoate version will be a specific intent crime (the specific intent to commit the target crime.)', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Criminal Intent, Part 1', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL);
INSERT INTO `records_lawcourse` (`id`, `uid`, `created`, `updated`, `status`, `lat`, `lng`, `title`, `description`, `details`, `path`, `deleted`, `users_info_id`, `location_id`, `admin_approved`, `i1`, `i2`, `i3`, `i4`, `d1`, `d2`, `d3`, `d4`, `vc1`, `vc2`, `vc3`, `vc4`, `t1`, `t2`, `t3`, `t4`, `parent_id`, `reference_id`, `expiry_dt`) VALUES
(148, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:53:11', '2016-05-29 00:53:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Causation', 'Proof that the defendantâ€™s act is the actual and proximate cause of harm is required in order to establish that a defendant should be found guilty of a crime that includes a harmful result.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. the prosecution must prove defendantâ€™s act is actual cause of harm\n2. the prosecution must prove defendantâ€™s act is proximate cause of harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Causation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(149, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:53:42', '2016-05-29 00:53:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Actual Cause (or Cause in Fact)', 'An actual cause is the cause which starts, ignites or makes possible the result which follows, and which satisfies the â€œBut For\\" or Substantial Factor Test.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. starts or ignites chain of events\n2. satisfies â€œBut Forâ€ or Substantial Factor Test', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Causation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(150, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:55:25', '2016-05-29 00:55:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'â€œBut Forâ€ Test', 'The â€œBut Forâ€ Test is used to establish actual cause in criminal cases which include a harmful result as an element of the crime. To apply the test, the state must show that â€œbut forâ€ the defendant\\''s act, the harm would not have occurred.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. used to establish actual cause\n2. â€œbut forâ€ defendantâ€™s act, harm would not have occurred', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Causation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(151, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:55:59', '2016-05-29 00:55:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Substantial Factor Test', 'The Substantial Factor Test is used to establish actual cause where more than one act contributes to the harm. The defendant is said to be an actual cause of the harm if the defendantâ€™s act is a substantial factor in bringing the harm about. This means that the defendant\\''s act contributed to more than a trivial degree to the resulting harm.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. used to establish actual cause\n2. more than one act is involved in producing harm\n3. defendantâ€™s act contributed to harm to more than a trivial degree', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Causation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(152, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 00:56:53', '2016-05-29 00:56:53', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Proximate Cause (or Cause in Law)', 'In criminal law, an actual cause of harm is also the proximate cause if the act is closely connected enough to the resulting harm that it is fair to hold the defendant responsible for causing the harm. Under the Model Penal Code, this means that the resulting harm is not â€œtoo remote or accidentalâ€ from the defendantâ€™s act to make it unfair to hold him responsible.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. act is already proven to be an actual cause of plaintiffâ€™s harm\n2. the resulting harm is not very remote nor accidental\n3. holding the defendant responsible is fair', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Causation', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(153, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 01:17:08', '2016-05-29 01:17:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Principal in the First Degree', 'Under common law, a principal in the first degree is one who personally performs the actus reus of the crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. personally performs actus reus', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(154, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 01:17:47', '2016-05-29 01:17:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Principal in the Second Degree', 'Under the common law, a principal in the second degree is one who does not personally perform any actus reus of the crime, but who is actually or constructively present and who aids and abets in the commission of the crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. does not personally perform any actus reus\n2. actually or constructively present\n3. aids and abets', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(155, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 01:18:08', '2016-05-29 01:18:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Principal', 'Modernly, most jurisdictions have abandoned the common law title of â€œprincipal in the first degreeâ€ and refer to the person who commits the actus reus of the crime simply as a â€œprincipal.â€\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. personally performs actus reus', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(156, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:20:36', '2016-05-29 02:20:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Constructive Presence', 'Constructive presence is presence that is legally imputed to one who, while not physically present during an act, is so situated as to give assistance to the perpetrator. For example, a lookout or the driver of a getaway car during a robbery is constructively present at the crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. legally imputed\n2. not physically present\n3. situated to give assistance', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(157, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:20:53', '2016-05-29 02:20:53', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Aid and Abet', 'To aid and abet means to knowingly or intentionally assist in or facilitate the commission of a crime.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(158, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:21:07', '2016-05-29 02:21:07', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Accessory', 'An accessory is one who knowingly counsels, commands, encourages, or aids in the perpetration of a crime, but who is not present during the actual crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. knowledge\n2. counsels, commands, encourages, or aids in perpetration\n3. not present during actus reus', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(159, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:21:22', '2016-05-29 02:21:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Accessory before the Fact', 'An accessory before the fact counsels, commands, encourages or assists prior to the actus reus of the crime and is not present during the commission of the crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. accessory\n2. prior to actus reus\n3. not present at crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(160, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:21:40', '2016-05-29 02:21:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Accessory after the Fact', 'An accessory after the fact is one who was not present during the commission of the crime, but who provides aid with knowledge that the crime was committed, for example, by aiding the felon in avoiding arrest, conviction or punishment.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. accessory\n2. after actus reus\n3. knowledge that crime was committed', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(161, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:22:05', '2016-05-29 02:22:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Accomplice', 'Modernly, most jurisdictions have abandoned the common law titles of "principal in the second degree" and "accessory before the fact," and refer to one who intentionally and knowingly participates or assists in the commission of a crime as an "accomplice." In the minority of jurisdictions which still use the term "accessory before the fact," an accomplice is one who participates or assists in a crime and who is present\nduring the crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentionally\n2. knowingly\n3. participates or assists in crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(164, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:00:28', '2016-05-29 13:00:28', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Compounding the Crime', 'Compounding the crime involves the acceptance of anything of value under an unlawful agreement not to prosecute a known offender, or to limit or to otherwise hinder the prosecution of his case.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. acceptance of anything of value\n2. agreement not to prosecute', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(162, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:24:02', '2016-05-29 02:24:02', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Accomplice Liability', 'Under the theory of accomplice liability, accomplices are guilty of the target crime and, in most jurisdictions, are also guilty of all acts by all accomplices or principals which are in furtherance of the target crime and all additional crimes which are a natural or probable consequence of the target crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. guilty of target crime\n2. guilty of crimes in furtherance of target crime\n3. guilty of crimes which are a natural and probable consequence of target crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(163, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 02:24:17', '2016-05-29 02:24:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Misprision of a Felony', 'Under common law, misprision of a felony is the nondisclosure of the known felony of another. However, modernly it is the concealment of a known felony of another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. concealment\n2. felony of another', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Persons involved in Criminal Acts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(165, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:00:59', '2016-05-29 13:00:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate', 'Inchoate means partly or imperfectly formed, or incomplete.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(166, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:01:16', '2016-05-29 13:01:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Solicitation', 'Solicitation occurs when one counsels, incites, solicits, or requests another to commit an unlawful act.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. counsels, incites, solicits, or requests\n2. to commit an unlawful act', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(167, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:16:59', '2016-05-29 13:16:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Attempt', 'An attempt occurs when criminal intent becomes accompanied by an act which comes within close proximity of committing a crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. criminal intent\n2. action taken\n3. close proximity of committing a crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(168, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:17:16', '2016-05-29 13:17:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Conspiracy', 'A conspiracy results when two or more persons agree together to accomplish a criminal or unlawful act or to do a lawful act by criminal or unlawful means.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n4. two or more persons\n5. agreement to accomplish\n6. criminal or unlawful act or lawful act by criminal or unlawful means', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(169, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:17:40', '2016-05-29 13:17:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Pinkertonâ€™s Rule', 'Under Pinkertonâ€™s Rule, each member of a conspiracy can be charged with crimes committed by co-conspirators if those crimes were committed in furtherance of the target crime or if they were a natural and probable consequence of the target crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. co-conspirators guilty of each otherâ€™s crimes if\na. in furtherance of target crime or\nb. natural and probable consequence of target crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(170, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:18:12', '2016-05-29 13:18:12', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Whartonâ€™s Rule', 'Under Whartonâ€™s Rule, when a crime requires the participation of more than one person, (e.g., dueling, bribery, etc.) the perpetrators cannot be charged with conspiracy. However, if there are more perpetrators than the crime, by definition, logically requires, then conspiracy can be charged.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. crime logically requires more than one perpetrator\n2. conspiracy does not apply', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Inchoate Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(171, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:18:50', '2016-05-29 13:18:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Battery', 'Battery is the intentional, harmful or offensive touching of another person.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. harmful or offensive\n3. touching of another person', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(172, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:19:11', '2016-05-29 13:19:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Assault', 'Assault is the intentional threatening of another with battery and the creating of reasonable apprehension of immediate bodily harm in the victim. Additionally, in criminal law, an assault is an attempted but failed battery regardless of whether the intended victim was aware of the attempt.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n4. a. intentional\nb. threat of battery\nc. creating reasonable apprehension of immediate bodily harm, or\n5. attempted but failed battery regardless of whether there was apprehension', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(173, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:19:22', '2016-05-29 13:19:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rape', 'Rape is sexual intercourse with a woman without her consent.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. sexual intercourse\n2. woman\n3. without consent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(174, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:19:34', '2016-05-29 13:19:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory Rape', 'Statutory rape is sexual intercourse with a willing female under the age of consent.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. sexual intercourse\n2. consensual\n3. female\n4. under the age of consent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(175, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:19:50', '2016-05-29 13:19:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Sodomy', 'Sodomy is the term used generically to cover what the common law or state legislatures regard as seriously \\"deviate\\" or \\"unnatural\\" sexual practices.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. deviate\n2. unnatural\n3. sexual practices', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(176, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:20:20', '2016-05-29 13:20:20', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mayhem', 'Mayhem is the malicious maiming or disfiguring of another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. malicious\n2. maiming or disfiguring', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(177, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:20:52', '2016-05-29 13:20:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'False Imprisonment', 'False imprisonment is the intentional confinement of another person against his will.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. confinement\n2. against personâ€™s will', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(178, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:21:09', '2016-05-29 13:21:09', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Kidnapping', 'Kidnapping is the movement of a person against his will from one place to another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. movement from one place to another\n2. against a personâ€™s will', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(179, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:21:21', '2016-05-29 13:21:21', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Homicide', 'Homicide is the killing of one human being by another human being.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. killing\n2. human being\n3. by another', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(180, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:21:38', '2016-05-29 13:21:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Murder', 'Murder is a homicide committed with malice aforethought.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. homicide\n2. with malice', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(181, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:22:32', '2016-05-29 13:22:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Malice Aforethought', 'Malice aforethought is the mens rea required for murder. It exists when the defendant has a \\"man endangering state of mind\\" as evidenced by one of the following intentions:\n1) an intent to kill as expressed by the defendant;\n2) an intent to cause serious bodily harm as implied by the defendantâ€™s actions;\n3) a wanton and willful disregard of human life (depraved or malignant heart) as implied by the defendantâ€™s actions; or\n4) an intent to commit a dangerous felony as implied by the defendantâ€™s actions.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intent to kill\n2. intent to cause serious bodily harm\n3. wanton, willful disregard for human life (depraved or malignant heart)\n4. intent to commit dangerous felony', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(182, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:22:48', '2016-05-29 13:22:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'First Degree Murder', 'First degree murder is murder committed by poison; torture; lying in wait; or other willful, deliberate and premeditated means; or murder that results from application of the Felony Murder Rule.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. murder\n2. committed by:\na. poison,\nb. torture,\nc. lying in wait,\nd. other willful, deliberate and premeditated means, or\ne. through application of the Felony Murder Rule', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(183, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:24:46', '2016-05-29 13:24:46', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Torture', 'Torture occurs when a person inflicts great bodily injury on another with intent to cause cruel or extreme pain and suffering for the purpose of revenge, extortion, persuasion, or for any sadistic purpose.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. infliction of great bodily injury\n2. on another person\n3. intent to cause cruel or extreme pain and suffering\n4. purpose is revenge, extortion, persuasion, or any sadistic purpose', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(184, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:24:57', '2016-05-29 13:24:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Willful', 'Willful means voluntary and intentional.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(185, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:25:06', '2016-05-29 13:25:06', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Deliberate', 'Deliberate means carefully considered.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(186, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:25:15', '2016-05-29 13:25:15', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Premeditated', 'Premeditated means thought out or planned beforehand.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(187, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:25:34', '2016-05-29 13:25:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Felony Murder Rule', 'Under the Felony Murder Rule, if a death occurs during the attempt or commission of a serious felony, is causally related to that felony, and is not a lesser included offense, then the felon can be charged with first degree murder.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. death occurs during attempt or commission of serious felony\n2. death is causally related to the felony\n3. the target felony is not a lesser included offense of the homicide', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(188, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:25:54', '2016-05-29 13:25:54', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Second Degree Murder', 'Second degree murder is all murders which are not first degree murder, in other words, those homicides committed with malice aforethought but which do not meet the requirements for murder in the first degree.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. murder\n2. with malice\n3. not first degree', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(189, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:26:07', '2016-05-29 13:26:07', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Voluntary Manslaughter', 'Voluntary manslaughter is a murder which, because of mitigating circumstances, is treated as less heinous than first or second degree murder.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. murder\n2. mitigating circumstances', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(190, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:26:21', '2016-05-29 13:26:21', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Heat of Passion', 'Heat of passion is one mitigating factor that can reduce a murder charge to voluntary manslaughter, if the defendant can prove the following elements:\n1) adequate provocation to lead a reasonable person to lose his normal self-control,\n2) the defendant actually lost his self-control, and\n3) there was not enough time for the defendant to cool off between the provocation and the murder.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant committed murder\n2. adequate provocation\n3. defendant lost self-control (subjective test)\n4. a reasonable person would lose self-control (objective test)\n5. no cool off period', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(191, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:26:42', '2016-05-29 13:26:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Involuntary Manslaughter', 'Involuntary manslaughter is an unintentional homicide committed without malice but under circumstances involving either gross negligence or the commission of a crime not covered by the Felony Murder Rule.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unintentional homicide\n2. no malice\n3. either:\na. gross negligence or\nb. during commission of a crime not covered by the felony murder rule', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes Against Persons', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(192, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:27:11', '2016-05-29 13:27:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Burglary', 'Burglary is the breaking and entering of the dwelling house of another in the nighttime with the intent to commit a felony therein.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. breaking\n2. entering\n3. dwelling\n4. of another\n5. nighttime\n6. intent to commit felony inside', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against real property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(193, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:27:23', '2016-05-29 13:27:23', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory Burglary', 'Statutory Burglary is an unlawful entry into a structure or vehicle with the intent to commit a felony or theft, including petty theft, once inside.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unlawful entry\n2. structure or vehicle\n3. intent to commit felony or theft inside', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against real property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(194, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:27:33', '2016-05-29 13:27:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Arson', 'Arson is the malicious burning of the dwelling house of another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. malicious\n2. burning\n3. dwelling\n4. of another', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against real property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(195, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:27:43', '2016-05-29 13:27:43', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Statutory Arson', 'Statutory arson is the malicious burning of any structure.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. malicious\n2. burning\n3. any structure', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against real property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(196, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:28:24', '2016-05-29 13:28:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Larceny', 'Larceny is the trespassory taking and carrying away of the personal property of another with intent to permanently deprive the owner thereof.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n4. trespassory taking\n5. carrying away\n6. personal property of another\n7. intent to permanently deprive', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(197, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:28:49', '2016-05-29 13:28:49', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Larceny by Trick', 'Larceny by trick is a form of larceny in which the taking of the personal property of another was done with the ownerâ€™s consent; however, the consent was obtained by deceit or fraud.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. larceny\n2. consent was given by owner to take property\n3. consent was obtained by fraud', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(198, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:29:05', '2016-05-29 13:29:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Obtaining Property by False Pretenses', 'Obtaining property by false pretenses is the obtaining of title to the property of another through a false representation of fact with the intent to defraud.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. obtaining title\n2. to anotherâ€™s property\n3. through false representations of fact\n4. intent to defraud', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(199, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:29:20', '2016-05-29 13:29:20', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Embezzlement', 'Embezzlement is the fraudulent taking of the personal property of another by one to whom possession has been entrusted.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. fraudulent taking\n2. personal property of another\n3. by one to whom possession was entrusted', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(200, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:29:36', '2016-05-29 13:29:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Robbery', 'Robbery is larceny from the person of another by use of violence, force, intimidation, or threat of immediate harm.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. larceny\n2. person of another\n3. violence, force, intimidation, or threat of immediate harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(201, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:29:51', '2016-05-29 13:29:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Extortion', 'Extortion is the unlawful obtaining of property from another through coercion, usually involving a threat to perform an illegal act in the future. In some states, the term â€œextortionâ€ applies to one acting in an official capacity or under color of office, while â€œblackmailâ€ applies to any person.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. obtaining property of another\n2. coercion (often by officials)\n3. threat of future illegal act', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(202, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:30:12', '2016-05-29 13:30:12', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Blackmail', 'Blackmail, in most states, is the same as extortion. However, in some states, extortion applies to those acting under color of office, while blackmail applies to any person obtaining property through coercion. In other states, blackmail applies to coercion through a threat to reveal information where such revelation would not be criminal in itself, but is only criminal because of the use of the threat to coerce the giving of property.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. obtaining property of another\n2. coercion\n3. threat of future illegal act or threat to reveal information', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(203, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:30:28', '2016-05-29 13:30:28', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Bribery', 'Bribery is the corrupt payment or receipt of an advantage or anything of value with an intent to influence a personâ€™s action, vote, or opinion, in any public or official capacity.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. corrupt payment or receipt\n2. intent to influence\n3. public or official capacity', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(204, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:30:39', '2016-05-29 13:30:39', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Forgery', 'Forgery is the false making or material alteration of any writing of legal significance with the intent to defraud.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. false making or material alteration\n2. writing of legal significance\n3. intent to defraud', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(205, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:30:56', '2016-05-29 13:30:56', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Uttering', 'Uttering is the use of a forged instrument, knowing that it is forged, with the intent to defraud.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. use of a forged instrument\n2. knowing that it is forged\n3. intent to defraud', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(206, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:31:11', '2016-05-29 13:31:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Receiving Stolen Property', 'Receiving stolen property is the acquisition of stolen property with knowledge at the time of receipt that it was stolen, when done with intent to deprive the owner of his or her property.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. acquisition of property\n2. stolen\n3. knowledge\n4. intent to deprive owner', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crimes against personal property and interests in property', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(207, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:31:45', '2016-05-29 13:31:45', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Perjury', 'Perjury is the making of a false oath or affirmation in a judicial proceeding in regard to a material matter.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. false oath or affirmation\n2. judicial proceeding', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(208, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:31:57', '2016-05-29 13:31:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Subornation of Perjury', 'Subornation of perjury is the procurement of perjury from another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. procurement of perjury', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(209, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:32:09', '2016-05-29 13:32:09', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Embracery', 'Embracery is an attempt by corrupt and wrongful means to influence a juror in regard to the jury\\''s verdict.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. attempt\n2. to influence a juror\n3. by corrupt and wrongful means', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(210, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:32:27', '2016-05-29 13:32:27', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Breach of Peace', 'A breach of peace is a willful act which unreasonably disturbs the public peace.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. willful act\n2. unreasonably disturbs the public peace', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(211, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:32:41', '2016-05-29 13:32:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Unlawful Assembly', 'An unlawful assembly is a meeting of three or more people with a common plan to commit an unlawful act or a lawful act in a manner likely to cause a breach of peace.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. meeting of three or more people\n2. common plan\na. unlawful act or\nb. lawful act in manner likely to cause a breach of peace', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(212, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:32:52', '2016-05-29 13:32:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rout', 'A rout is the movement of unlawful assemblers for the purpose of carrying out the common design.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. movement of unlawful assemblers\n2. to carry out the common design', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(213, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:33:03', '2016-05-29 13:33:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Riot', 'A riot is a tumultuous breach of peace by three or more persons acting together to commit a crime by open force or to carry out any common enterprise.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. tumultuous breach of peace\n2. by three or more persons', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(214, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:33:13', '2016-05-29 13:33:13', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Affray', 'An affray is a mutual fight in a public place.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mutual fight\n2. public place', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miscellaneous Crimes', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(215, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:34:24', '2016-05-29 13:34:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Infancy', 'Under the defense of infancy, a child under the age of 7 does not have the capacity to commit a crime, there is a rebuttable presumption that a child aged 7 to 14 does not have the capacity to commit a crime, and a child over the age of 14 has the same capacity to commit a crime that an adult has.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. under age 7: lacks criminal capacity\n2. ages 7 to 14: rebuttable presumption of lack of criminal capacity\n3. over age 14: same criminal capacity as an adult', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(216, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:34:37', '2016-05-29 13:34:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Unconsciousness', 'Under the defense of unconsciousness, a person who is unconscious, for instance, someone who is sleep walking, does not have the capacity to commit a crime.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unconscious\n2. lacks criminal capacity', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(217, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:41:28', '2016-05-29 13:41:28', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Involuntary Intoxication', 'Under the defense of involuntary intoxication, if a person is unintentionally intoxicated on alcohol or drugs as a result of force, fraud, medical prescription, reasonable mistake, allergic reaction, or the like, then his or her actions are excused to the same extent as they would be if those actions were the result of a mental disorder.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unintentional intoxication\n2. actions excused to same extent as would be if caused by a mental disorder', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(218, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:41:42', '2016-05-29 13:41:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Voluntary Intoxication', 'Under the defense of voluntary intoxication, a defendant who is intentionally intoxicated will be excused for his or her actions only if the intoxication has developed into a permanent mental disorder. However, voluntary intoxication may mitigate the degree or severity of the crime or charge if, due to the intoxication, the requisite criminal intent is lacking.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional intoxication\n2. complete defense only if developed into a permanent mental disorder\n3. mitigation if it negates criminal intent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(219, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:42:17', '2016-05-29 13:42:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The M\\''Naghten Rule or The Right vs. Wrong Test of Insanity', 'Under the M\\''Naghten Rule, a defendant is entitled to the defense of insanity if he suffers from a mental disease of the mind and does not know what he is doing or does not know that what he is doing is wrong. Also, a defendant is entitled to the defense of insanity if he suffers from an insane delusion and if the notion embodied in the delusion and believed to be a fact would excuse the defendant had the notion been true.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mental disease of the mind\na. does not know what he is doing, or\nb. does not know that what he is doing is wrong, or\nc. i. suffers from an insane delusion, and\nii. the notion believed to be a fact would excuse the defendant had the notion been true', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(220, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:42:30', '2016-05-29 13:42:30', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Insane Delusion', 'An insane delusion is the product of a mental disorder in which the defendant has a false belief in something that would be incredible to others and that belief remains persistent despite proof to the contrary.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. product of a mental disorder\n2. false belief in something incredible\n3. remains persistent to the defendant', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(221, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:42:43', '2016-05-29 13:42:43', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The Irresistible Impulse Test', 'Under the Irresistible Impulse Test, a defendant is entitled to the defense of insanity if, because of a mental disorder, he knows that he is doing wrong but cannot control his behavior.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mental disorder\n2. knows what he is doing wrong\n3. cannot control his behavior', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(222, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:43:01', '2016-05-29 13:43:01', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The Substantial Capacity Test or Model Penal Code Test', 'Under the Substantial Capacity Test or Model Penal Code Test, a defendant is entitled to the defense of insanity if at the time of his conduct, as a result of a mental disease or defect, he lacks substantial capacity to appreciate the wrongfulness of his conduct or the capacity to conform his conduct to the requirements of the law.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mental disease or defect\na. lacks substantial capacity to appreciate the wrongfulness of his conduct, or\nb. lacks capacity to conform his conduct to the requirements of the law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(223, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:43:33', '2016-05-29 13:43:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The Durham Rule or Product Rule', 'Under the Durham Rule, also known as the Product Rule, a defendant is entitled to the defense of insanity if, because of a mental disease or defect, he committed an unlawful act.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mental disease or defect\n2. commits unlawful act', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(224, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:43:53', '2016-05-29 13:43:53', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The Diminished Capacity Test or Wells-Gorshen Rule', 'Under the Diminished Capacity Test, also known as the Wells-Gorshen Rule, evidence of mental infirmity not amounting to insanity is admissible and should be considered on questions of premeditation, deliberation, and malice, although diminished capacity is not a complete defense.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. not a complete defense\n2. mental infirmity not amounting to insanity\n3. should be considered on questions of premeditation, deliberation and malice', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses related to lack of criminal capacity', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(225, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:44:21', '2016-05-29 13:44:21', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Self-Defense', 'A person who reasonably believes himself to be threatened with immediate bodily harm may use whatever degree of force is apparently necessary to protect himself. If the attack is with so-called â€œdeadly forceâ€ the majority rule is that the one attacked may defend with â€œdeadly forceâ€ if deemed reasonable under the circumstances. The minority rule requires that the one attacked retreat if there is a safe means of doing so, unless the victim of the attack is in his â€œcastleâ€ (i.e., home).\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. objectively reasonable belief of threat to self of immediate bodily harm\n2. degree of force is apparently necessary', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(226, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:44:38', '2016-05-29 13:44:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Defense of Others', 'A person who reasonably believes another to be threatened with immediate bodily harm may use whatever degree of force is apparently necessary to protect the personal safety of the other person.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. objectively reasonable belief of threat to another of immediate bodily harm\n2. degree of force is apparently necessary', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(227, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:47:13', '2016-05-29 13:47:13', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Step-In-Shoes Jurisdiction (Defense of Others)', 'In some jurisdictions a person is not allowed to use the defense of â€œdefense of othersâ€ unless the person being defended was not the aggressor and had the right to use self-defense.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant claims the defense of others\n2. person defended was not aggressor\n3. person defended was entitled to use self-defense', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL);
INSERT INTO `records_lawcourse` (`id`, `uid`, `created`, `updated`, `status`, `lat`, `lng`, `title`, `description`, `details`, `path`, `deleted`, `users_info_id`, `location_id`, `admin_approved`, `i1`, `i2`, `i3`, `i4`, `d1`, `d2`, `d3`, `d4`, `vc1`, `vc2`, `vc3`, `vc4`, `t1`, `t2`, `t3`, `t4`, `parent_id`, `reference_id`, `expiry_dt`) VALUES
(228, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:47:48', '2016-05-29 13:47:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Reasonable Appearances Jurisdictions (Defense of Others)', 'In other jurisdictions, a person defending another in good faith and in ignorance of the fact that the person being defended is the aggressor and not entitled to use self-defense is nevertheless justified when acting upon reasonable appearances. Sometimes it is further required that the person being defended is one whom the defender is authorized by statute to protect.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant claims defense of others\n2. defendant acted in good faith\n3. objectively reasonable ignorance of the fact that the person being defended was aggressor', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(229, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:48:10', '2016-05-29 13:48:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Defense of Property', 'A person may use reasonable force that is not likely to cause death or serious bodily harm to protect his or her possession of real or personal property against an apparent trespasser.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts to protect his property from being taken\n2. taking is apparently trespassory\n3. degree of force used was objectively reasonable and not life-threatening', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(230, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:48:25', '2016-05-29 13:48:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Prevention of Crime', 'A person, whether a police officer or private person, may use reasonable force to prevent the commission of a crime which is apparently being attempted in his or her presence.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. reasonable belief that a crime is being committed in defendantâ€™s presence\n2. defendant acted to prevent the crime\n3. degree of force used was objectively reasonable', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(231, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:48:41', '2016-05-29 13:48:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Legal Authority', 'A person may commit an otherwise criminal act if it is done under legal process or is otherwise authorized by law.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts under legal process or otherwise authorized by law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(232, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:49:00', '2016-05-29 13:49:00', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Necessity', 'A person may commit an otherwise criminal act if that person is acting in an emergency situation to protect himself or others from a threatened injury to person or property. The person claiming the defense of necessity may act on appearances. A reasonable mistake is permitted.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts to protect himself, others, or property\n2. defendant had an objectively reasonable belief that his act was done during an emergency situation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(233, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:49:18', '2016-05-29 13:49:18', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Duress', 'A person may commit an otherwise criminal act if his act was the result of a reasonable fear of imminent death or serious bodily harm and if his fear was induced by a threat made by a third person. However, this defense will not apply to an intentional killing of another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. threat made by third person\n2. defendant has reasonable fear\n3. imminent death or serious bodily harm\n4. not applicable to intentional homicide', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(234, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:49:37', '2016-05-29 13:49:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Entrapment', 'A person may not be convicted of a crime if a law enforcement officer (or an agent of an officer) solicited, induced or encouraged the person to commit the crime and if the person would not otherwise have committed it.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. law enforcement officer or agent thereof solicits, induces or encourages the commission of a crime\n2. accused did not have pre-existing intent to commit such crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(235, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:49:55', '2016-05-29 13:49:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Mistake of Fact', 'A mistake of fact will disprove a criminal charge if it is honestly entertained, based upon reasonable grounds and is of such a nature that the conduct would have been lawful had the facts been as they were supposed to be.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. honestly entertained\n2. based upon reasonable grounds\n3. conduct would have been lawful had the facts been as supposed', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(236, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 13:50:15', '2016-05-29 13:50:15', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Mistake of Law', 'A mistake of law is not a valid defense to a crime except in those rare instances where it negates an essential element of the crime. Therefore, the old saying \\"ignorance of the law is no excuse\\" is appropriate as a general rule.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. ignorance of the law is no excuse', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(237, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:01:51', '2016-05-29 14:01:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Battery', 'Battery is the intentional, harmful or offensive touching of another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. harmful or offensive\n3. touching of another person', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(238, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:03:01', '2016-05-29 14:03:01', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Assault', 'Assault is the intentional threatening of another with battery and the creating of reasonable apprehension of immediate bodily harm in the victim.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. threat of battery\n3. creating reasonable apprehension of immediate bodily harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(239, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:03:10', '2016-05-29 14:03:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'False Imprisonment', 'False imprisonment is the intentional confinement of the plaintiff by the defendant.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. confinement of another person', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(240, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:04:36', '2016-05-29 14:04:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Infliction of Mental Distress', 'Intentional infliction of mental (or emotional) distress, is the intentional causing of severe emotional or mental distress in another through extreme and outrageous conduct.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. causing another person severe emotional or mental distress\n3. extreme and outrageous conduct', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(241, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:04:49', '2016-05-29 14:04:49', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Trespass to Land', 'Trespass to land is an intentional entry upon real property in the possession of another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. entry upon real property\n3. in possession of another', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(242, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:05:08', '2016-05-29 14:05:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Trespass to Chattel', 'Trespass to chattel is the intentional interference with a personâ€™s use or possession of a chattel.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. interference with chattel\n3. possessed by another', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(243, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:05:24', '2016-05-29 14:05:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Conversion', 'Conversion is an intentional assumption of dominion and control over the chattel of another, resulting in a substantial interference with the plaintiff\\''s possessory rights.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intentional\n2. dominion and control of a chattel\n3. possessed by another\n4. substantial interference with possessory rights', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(244, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:17:36', '2016-05-29 14:17:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Intent Requirement for Intentional Torts', 'In order to find that a tortious act was done with intent, it must be established that the defendant had a conscious desire that the result would occur, knew that the result would occur, or knew that the result was substantially certain to occur.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. conscious desire to produce result, or\n2. knowledge that result will occur, or\n3. knowledge that result is substantially certain to occur', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Concepts and Doctrines related to the Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(245, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:17:54', '2016-05-29 14:17:54', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Substantial Certainty Doctrine', 'The Substantial Certainty Doctrine holds that if the defendant does an act with the knowledge that it is substantially certain to produce a particular result, the defendant is deemed to have intended the result and is liable for his act.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts\n2. defendant knows his act is substantially certain to produce result', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Concepts and Doctrines related to the Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(246, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:18:16', '2016-05-29 14:18:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Transferred Intent Doctrine', 'The Transferred Intent Doctrine is applicable when a defendant, while in the process of committing a tort against one person, unintentionally harms a third person or commits a different tort. In such a case, the defendantâ€™s wrongful intent is transferred to include the unintended victim or tortious act.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant intends to commit a tortious act\n2. a. result is harm to a different victim than intended, or\nb. result is a different tort than intended', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Concepts and Doctrines related to the Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(247, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:18:33', '2016-05-29 14:18:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Trespass Ab Initio', 'Trespass ab initio is an entry upon the real property in possession of another under a conferred legal right, and the subsequent abusing of that conferred legal right through the commission of an assault, battery, false imprisonment, or trespass.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. legal entry upon anotherâ€™s property\n2. abuse of right of entry by commission of tort', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Concepts and Doctrines related to the Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(248, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:20:08', '2016-05-29 14:20:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Consent', 'A defendant who acted in accordance with the plaintiffâ€™s informed and voluntary assent, whether express or implied, is not liable for the resulting harm so long as the plaintiff had legal capacity.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. informed\n2. voluntary\n3. express or implied assent\n4. legal capacity', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(249, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:20:48', '2016-05-29 14:20:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Self-Defense', 'A person who reasonably believes himself to be threatened with immediate bodily harm may use whatever degree of force is apparently necessary to protect himself. \n\nIf the attack is with so-called \\"deadly force\\" the majority rule is that the one attacked may defend with \\"deadly force\\" if deemed reasonable under the circumstances. The minority rule requires that the one attacked retreat if there is a safe means of doing so, unless the victim of the attack is in his \\"castle\\"(i.e., home).\n\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. objectively reasonable belief of threat to self of immediate bodily harm\n2. degree of force is apparently necessary', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(250, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:23:34', '2016-05-29 14:23:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Defense of Others', 'A person who reasonably believes another to be threatened with immediate bodily harm may use whatever degree of force is apparently necessary to protect the personal safety of the other person.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. objectively reasonable belief of threat to another of immediate bodily harm\n2. degree of force is apparently necessary', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(251, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:23:50', '2016-05-29 14:23:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Step-In-Shoes Jurisdiction (Defense of Others)', 'In some jurisdictions a person is not allowed to use the defense of â€œdefense of othersâ€ unless the person being defended was not the aggressor and had the right to use self-defense.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant claims the defense of others\n2. person defended was not aggressor\n3. person defended was entitled to use self-defense', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(252, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:24:22', '2016-05-29 14:24:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Reasonable Appearances Jurisdictions (Defense of Others)', 'In other jurisdictions, a person defending another in good faith and in ignorance of the fact that the person being defended is the aggressor and not entitled to use self-defense is nevertheless justified when acting upon reasonable appearances. Sometimes it is further required that the person being defended is one whom the defender is authorized by statute to protect.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant claims defense of others\n2. defendant acted in good faith\n3. objectively reasonable ignorance of fact that person being defended was aggressor', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(253, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:24:42', '2016-05-29 14:24:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Defense of Property', 'A person may use reasonable force that is not likely to cause death or serious bodily harm to protect his or her possession of real or personal property against an apparent trespasser.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts to protect his property from being taken\n2. taking was apparently trespassory\n3. degree of force used was objectively reasonable and not life-threatening', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(254, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:24:55', '2016-05-29 14:24:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Prevention of Crime', 'A person, whether a police officer or a private person, may use reasonable force to prevent the commission of a crime which is apparently being attempted in his or her presence.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. reasonable belief that a crime is being committed in defendantâ€™s presence\n2. defendant acted to prevent the crime\n3. degree of force used was objectively reasonable', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(255, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:26:36', '2016-05-29 14:26:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Legal Authority', 'A person may commit an otherwise tortious act if it is done under legal process or is otherwise authorized by law. It is a defense that is usually used by police officers or private persons who have made an arrest either with or without a warrant and who are now facing charges of false imprisonment in relation to their having made the arrest.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts under legal process or otherwise authorized by law', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(256, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:26:59', '2016-05-29 14:26:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Necessity', 'A person may commit an otherwise tortious act if that person is acting in an emergency situation to protect himself or others from a threatened injury to person or property. The person claiming the defense of necessity may act on appearances. A reasonable mistake is permitted.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant acts to protect himself, others, or property\n2. defendant had an objectively reasonable belief that his act was done during an emergency situation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(257, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:27:39', '2016-05-29 14:27:39', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Defense of Recovery of Property', 'A person may commit an act which would otherwise be tortious if he or she is acting in fresh pursuit and with a reasonable degree of force to regain possession of his or her property. There are three separate aspects to this particular defense: re-entry upon land, recapture of chattel, and the Shopkeeper\\''s Rule.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendantâ€™s property has been taken\n2. defendant is in fresh pursuit\n3. defendant acts to regain his property\n4. degree of force was objectively reasonable and not life-threatening or likely to cause serious bodily harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(258, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:27:58', '2016-05-29 14:27:58', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Re-entry Upon Land Aspect', 'A person may use reasonable force to re-enter real property only if the taking of the property was tortious or wrongful and the re-entering party is entitled to immediate possession. Ordinarily, a demand must be made for the occupier to vacate unless such a demand would be a total exercise in futility. Only force not likely to cause death or serious bodily harm may be used.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendantâ€™s real property has been taken by another\n2. taking was wrongful or tortious\n3. defendant made a demand for the property to be vacated (unless futile)\n4. defendant acts to retake possession\n5. degree of force was\na. objectively reasonable and\nb. not life-threatening or likely to cause serious bodily harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(259, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:28:19', '2016-05-29 14:28:19', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Recapture of Chattel Aspect', 'A person may use reasonable force to defend against his or her chattel being taken only if the taking of the chattel was wrongful or tortious, the recapturing person is in fresh pursuit, and the degree of force is not likely to cause death or serious bodily harm.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendantâ€™s chattel has been taken\n2. taking was wrongful or tortious\n3. defendant is in fresh pursuit\n4. defendant acts to regain his property\n5. degree of force was\na. objectively reasonable and\nb. not life-threatening or likely to cause serious bodily harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(260, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:28:35', '2016-05-29 14:28:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Shopkeeper\\''s Rule', 'Under the Shopkeeperâ€™s Rule, a business person has a limited privilege in some jurisdictions to detain a suspected thief, e.g., shoplifter or embezzling employee, to investigate the shopkeeper\\''s claim to the goods, even though it may be determined that no wrongful taking has been committed.\r\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\r\n1. defendant is a business person\r\n2. objectively reasonable belief that a chattel has been taken by the plaintiff\r\n3. fresh pursuit\r\n4. defendant is charged with false imprisonment for detaining the suspected\r\nthief\r\n5. detention was for a reasonable length of time to conduct a reasonable\r\ninvestigation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(261, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:29:24', '2016-05-29 14:29:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Fresh Pursuit', 'Fresh pursuit relates to the requirement that a person recapturing a chattel or a shopkeeper detaining a suspected thief must do so without unreasonable delay after discovering the loss.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(262, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:29:43', '2016-05-29 14:29:43', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Reasonableness', 'Reasonableness is a concept that permeates all of the defenses to intentional torts. It is the standard by which the amount of force used or the time and manner of a re-entry, recapture, or detention is judged.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Defenses to Intentional Torts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(263, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:30:10', '2016-05-29 14:30:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Negligence', 'Liability for negligence requires proof of a duty of care owed by the defendant to the plaintiff, a breach of that duty, and that the breach was the actual and proximate cause of damages suffered by the plaintiff.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. duty\n2. breach\n3. causation\n4. damages', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Negligence', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(264, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:30:35', '2016-05-29 14:30:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'General Duty', 'The general rule of duty holds that everyone owes a duty to exercise due care so as not to subject others to unreasonable risks of harm.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. everyone owes duty of due care\n2. not to subject others to unreasonable risks of harm', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(265, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:32:08', '2016-05-29 14:32:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Cardozo Rule on Duty', 'Under Palsgraf v. Long Island Railroad Co., Justice Cardozoâ€™s majority opinion held that a defendant owes a duty only to those who could foreseeably be endangered by the defendantâ€™s negligent act. Therefore, according to the rule, there is no duty owed to a plaintiff who is in a position of apparent safety when the defendant commits a negligent act. This is the so-called â€œorbit of dangerâ€ test.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. duty owed to foreseeable plaintiffs in the â€œzone of dangerâ€', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(266, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:32:53', '2016-05-29 14:32:53', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Andrews Rule on Duty', 'In the Palsgraf case, Justice Andrews gave a dissenting opinion which has been applied as the majority opinion in other cases. Andrews argued that if the defendant owes a duty to anyone, then he owes a duty to everyone who could foreseeably be injured by his action. Thus, Cardozo looked at the issue from a perspective of identifying whether a duty is owed, while Andrews considered the issue as one of proximate causation.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. liability imposed upon defendant for any harm proximately caused by defendantâ€™s act', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(267, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:40:27', '2016-05-29 14:40:27', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Special Duty', 'In addition to the general duty which everyone owes, special duties may be imposed due to a special relationship or circumstance.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. special relationship or circumstance may raise a special duty', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(268, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:40:52', '2016-05-29 14:40:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Negligence Per Se', 'Under the doctrine of negligence per se, the elements of duty and breach are proved when a defendant violates a safety statute which was intended to protect the class of people to which the plaintiff belongs from the kind of injury the defendant caused. In California, a presumption of negligence arises.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant violates safety statute\n2. plaintiff is a member of the class that the statute was designed to protect\n3. injury to plaintiff is the type the statute was enacted to prevent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(269, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:42:57', '2016-05-29 14:42:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Guest Passenger', 'A driver of a motor vehicle, in the absence of a statute otherwise, owes to persons riding in the vehicle a duty of driving with due care. However, a number of jurisdictions have statutes that provide that a guest passenger in an automobile cannot recover from the owner or operator of the automobile unless the owner or operator is guilty of willful misconduct, recklessness, or intoxication.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. drivers owe a duty to passengers to drive with due care', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(270, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:56:49', '2016-05-29 14:56:49', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Person Injured by a Drunk Driver', 'A person who serves alcoholic beverages to one who is intoxicated is not, in the absence of a statute stating otherwise, liable for the damages done by the intoxicated person. However, in those jurisdictions which have statutes traditionally referred to as dram shop acts, an owner, a bartender or other persons serving alcoholic beverages to a person who is intoxicated can be held liable for the foreseeable damages caused by the intoxicated person.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. no duty to avoid serving alcohol, even if recipient is intoxicated\n2. exception: under dram shop acts, persons serving alcohol owe a duty of care\nto those injured by one who is intoxicated', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(271, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 14:57:01', '2016-05-29 14:57:01', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Owner Liability Statutes', 'Certain statutes impose liability upon owners of vehicles for the tortious acts committed by persons to whom the owner intentionally furnishes the vehicle.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. vehicle owner may owe duty to those injured by person to whom vehicle was\nloaned', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(272, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:05:48', '2016-05-29 15:05:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Family Purpose Doctrine', 'A parent who furnishes a vehicle to the members of his or her family for customary convenience, assumes liability for the tortious acts committed by those persons when the car is being driven for a family purpose.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. parent owes duty to those injured by family members who use vehicle\n2. vehicle used for family purpose', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(273, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:06:05', '2016-05-29 15:06:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Omission to Act', 'An omission to act to prevent injury, or â€œnonfeasanceâ€ as it is sometimes called, does not give rise to tort liability unless there is a special relationship or special circumstance which creates an affirmative duty requiring the defendant to act to protect the plaintiff.\r\nAn affirmative duty to act may arise when there is a close familial relationship, such as parent and child or husband and wife; when the defendant and the plaintiff are coventurers; when the defendant caused the plaintiff to be in danger or injured; when the defendant has begun to render assistance to the plaintiff; when the defendant fails to perform a duty to control the behavior of others; when the defendant is an innkeeper; or when the defendant operates a common carrier such as a plane or ship.\r\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\r\n1. no duty is owed to act to prevent injury to another\r\n2. exceptions:\r\na. parent/child\r\nb. husband/wife\r\nc. co-venturers\r\nd. innkeeper/guest\r\ne. common carrier/passenger\r\nf. person who creates danger/person so endangered', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(274, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:07:41', '2016-05-29 15:07:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed by a Good Samaritan', 'A person who embarks upon the performance of services for another, whether gratuitously or for consideration, is under a duty to render those services with due care. This person, however, is under no duty to complete the performance of the services unless abandonment would prejudice the other party\\''s position. The rendering of aid in an emergency constitutes the performance of services, and a duty of care is imposed upon those who undertake to render such aid. Some jurisdictions have enacted statutes designed to encourage physicians to render emergency aid, by limiting the liability that could otherwise be imposed upon them. Generally speaking, liability can be imposed upon them only for reckless or wanton misconduct.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. person rendering services owes a duty of care to recipient of services\n2. abandonment is allowed unless it results in prejudice to the other partyâ€™s position', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(275, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:07:55', '2016-05-29 15:07:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Rescuer', 'A person whose negligence creates a situation in which he needs to be rescued may be held liable for injuries incurred by his rescuer.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. a person who creates situation in which rescue is needed owes a duty to rescuer', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(276, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:08:19', '2016-05-29 15:08:19', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Negligent Supervision', 'Negligent supervision is a cause of action which is brought by a plaintiff who suffered injury because a child or other person was inadequately supervised by one who owed a duty of supervision. Most commonly, it is brought against parents who failed to exercise ordinary parental discretion as to the manner in which their child is supervised or cared for.\nModernly, a child may bring an action against his or her own parents for injuries sustained by the child because of lack of proper supervision.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. person who is obligated to supervise a child owes a duty to those injured by child\n2. person who is obligated to supervise a child owes a duty to the child', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(277, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:08:37', '2016-05-29 15:08:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to an Invitee', 'A land occupier owes a duty of ordinary care to invitees, which includes reasonably inspecting the land for dangerous conditions and repairing those dangerous conditions which a reasonable inspection would reveal.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupier owes duty of care to invitee:\na. inspect land\nb. repair dangerous conditions', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(278, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:08:48', '2016-05-29 15:08:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Invitee', 'An invitee is a person who has an express or implied invitation to enter property for the purpose for which the property is maintained.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. enters land of another\n2. for purpose related to express or implied consent of owner', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(279, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:09:15', '2016-05-29 15:09:15', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Business Invitee', 'A business invitee is a person who has express or implied permission to enter business property to do business with the land occupier.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. enters business property of another\n2. for business purpose\n3. express or implied consent of occupier', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(280, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:09:35', '2016-05-29 15:09:35', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Public Invitee', 'A public invitee enters property in the possession of another for the purpose for which the property is held open to the public. It is not required that a business purpose be involved. Public employees acting within the scope of their official duties are included in the category of public invitees.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. enters real property which is open to public\n2. for purpose land is open\n3. no business purpose required', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(281, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:14:37', '2016-05-29 15:14:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Licensee', 'A landowner owes a duty of ordinary care to licensees, which includes either 1) warning licensees of known dangerous conditions, unless they are obvious or already known to the licensee, or 2) repairing dangerous conditions to make the property safe.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupier owes duty to licensee:\na. warn of dangerous conditions known to occupier and not known to licensee, unless obvious, or\nb. repair dangerous condition', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(282, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:19:51', '2016-05-29 15:19:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Licensee', 'A licensee is a person who enters property with the express or implied permission of the land occupier. Such entry is not for the purpose of doing business.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. enters real property of another\n2. express or implied consent\n3. entry is not for business purpose', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(283, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:20:07', '2016-05-29 15:20:07', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Trespasser', 'The land occupier generally owes no duty of care to the trespasser unless the trespasser is a constant trespasser upon a limited area or a child to whom the Attractive Nuisance Doctrine applies.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupier owes no duty to trespasser\n2. exceptions:\na. constant trespasser upon a limited area\nb. Attractive Nuisance Doctrine', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(284, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:20:32', '2016-05-29 15:20:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Trespasser', 'A trespasser is someone who enters the real property of another without express or implied consent.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. enters real property of another\n2. no consent', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(285, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:20:47', '2016-05-29 15:20:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Constant Trespasser Upon a Limited Area', 'The land occupier owes a duty to a constant trespasser upon a limited area of warning him of known dangerous artificial conditions unless such conditions are obvious.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupier owes duty to constant trespasser upon a limited area:\na. warn of dangerous artificial conditions known to land occupier unless obvious', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(286, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:21:09', '2016-05-29 15:21:09', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Constant Trespasser Upon a Limited Area', 'A constant trespasser upon a limited area is a trespasser whose presence is known, or should be known, to land occupier because of the trespasser\\''s repeated acts of trespassing.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. enters real property of another repeatedly in same area or manner\n2. no consent\n3. land occupier is aware of trespass or should be aware', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(287, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:21:40', '2016-05-29 15:21:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Child Trespasser', 'The land occupier owes no duty to a child trespasser unless he is a constant trespasser upon a limited area or unless the case is one in which the Attractive Nuisance Doctrine applies.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupier owes no duty to child trespasser\n2. exceptions:\na. constant trespasser upon a limited area\nb. Attractive Nuisance Doctrine', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(288, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:22:16', '2016-05-29 15:22:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Attractive Nuisance Doctrine', 'The Attractive Nuisance Doctrine, recognized in most jurisdictions, imposes a duty upon land occupiers for the protection of young children whose trespasses are to be anticipated and whose immaturity renders them particularly susceptible to injury from dangerous conditions on the land. The land occupier owes a duty of reasonable care to eliminate a danger or to otherwise protect children when the following elements are present:\r\n1) foreseeability of trespass,\r\n2) foreseeability of serious harm,\r\n3) the child is unaware of the danger, and\r\n4) the benefit to the owner of maintaining the condition in its dangerous form is slight when weighed against the risk to children.\r\n\r\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\r\n1. trespass by children is foreseeable\r\n2. serious harm is foreseeable\r\n3. child is unaware of the danger\r\n4. the benefit to the owner of maintaining the condition in its dangerous form is slight when weighed against the risk to children', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(289, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:23:11', '2016-05-29 15:23:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed to a Person Off the Premises', 'The land occupier owes a duty to maintain the premises in a reasonably safe condition for the protection of passersby and occupiers of adjoining premises. This includes the duty of inspection to discover and correct those defects which a reasonable inspection would reveal.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupier owes duty to those outside his property:\na. inspect for defects\nb. repair defects that should have been discovered by reasonable inspection', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(290, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:23:34', '2016-05-29 15:23:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rowland v. Christian', 'Under Rowland v. Christian, the court eliminated the distinction between business invitee, licensee, and trespasser, and found that the land occupier owes a duty to act as a \\"reasonable man\\" for the purposes of rendering the occupied property safe for others.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. land occupiers must act reasonably to keep their property in safe condition', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(291, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:24:03', '2016-05-29 15:24:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Natural Conditions', 'A land occupier traditionally owed no duty to others for the care of natural conditions on the occupied property. However, the recent trend may be to impose a duty of reasonable care as to natural conditions, at least in those situations where the condition is known to the landowner.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. traditional rule: land occupier owes no duty to care for, repair, or warn of dangers related to natural conditions\n2. recent trend: duty may be owed to give reasonable care for safety of others related to natural conditions', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(292, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:25:16', '2016-05-29 15:25:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed by Lessees and Lessors of Land', 'A lessee is a land occupier and has the same liabilities that any land occupier would have. A landlord owes no duty to a person coming onto land with the consent of the lessee, with the following exceptions:\n1) the lessor owes a duty if a danger exists at the start of the lease which the lessor knows or should know about and which the lessee has no reason to know about;\n2) the lessor has the duty to inspect for and repair dangerous conditions, if the lessor knows the lessee will hold the land open to the public;\n3) the lessor has a duty to use reasonable care to make common areas safe;\n4) the lessor owes a duty to keep the premises in good repair if that is part of the lease contract;\n5) the lessor owes a duty if he begins repairs and performs them unreasonably or does not finish them;\n6) the lessor owes a general duty of care in some jurisdictions.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. lessee is a land occupier and owes duties as such\n2. landlord owes no duty to those entering the property with consent of lessee\n3. exceptions:\na. danger is known or should be known to lessor at start of lease; lessee has no reason to know\nb. if lessor knows lessee will hold the land open to public: lessor owes same duty to business invitees that land occupier owes\nc. common areas: lessor owes reasonable duty of care\nd. lease contract designates lessor as responsible for premises: lessor owes duty to repair\ne. lessor begins repair: lessor owes duty to complete repairs reasonably\nf. in some jurisdictions: lessor owes general duty of care', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Duty Owed by Lessees and Lessors of Land', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(293, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-29 15:25:32', '2016-05-29 15:25:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'A breach is the failure to perform oneâ€™s duty.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. failure to perform duty', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL);
