(415, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:43:27', '2016-05-30 18:43:27', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Exceptions to the Statute of Frauds', 'A contract is exempt from the Statute of\nFraudsâ€”that is, a signed writing is not requiredâ€”in the following circumstances:\n1) a sufficient memorandum of the agreement is available;\n2) part performance of the contract has occurred; however, the contract may be enforceable only to the extent of completed performance;\n3) the doctrine of promissory estoppel can be justly applied;\n4) the contract involves payment of anotherâ€™s debt or default, but the main purpose of the contract was a different purpose;\n5) the contract cannot be fully performed within one year, but one party has already fully performed; or\n6) under the UCC, where:\na) a sales confirmation signed by the sender was received but not objected to within 10 days of receipt;\nb) the contract deals with goods to be specially manufactured and the seller has made either a substantial beginning of their manufacture or commitments for their procurement prior to receiving repudiation;\nc) the party against whom enforcement is sought admits in court that a contract was made, but the contract is not enforceable beyond the quantity of goods admitted;\nd) payment has been made, but the contract is not enforceable beyond the payment; or\ne) the goods have been received and accepted, but the contract is not enforceable beyond the quantity of goods received and accepted.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. Exceptions to the Statute of Frauds exist for:\na. sufficient memorandum\nb. part performance\nc. promissory estoppel\nd. main purpose doctrine\ne. full performance\nf. under the UCC, where:\ni. a sales confirmation signed by the sender, not objected to within 10 days,\nii. specially manufactured goods for which the seller has substantial beginning or commitments,\niii. admission in court that contract was made\niv. payment already made\nv. goods received and accepted', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Issues Affecting Formation of Contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(416, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:43:45', '2016-05-30 18:43:45', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Ambiguity', 'A contract is ambiguous when, examining the contract as a whole in light of the circumstances at the time of its creation, the meaning of the contract is uncertain or material terms of the contract could reasonably be interpreted in two or more inconsistent ways.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. meaning is uncertain or subject to two or more interpretations', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Issues Affecting Formation of Contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(417, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:44:03', '2016-05-30 18:44:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Illegality', 'If the subject matter of a contract is unlawful, the contract is unenforceable.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. subject matter unlawful\n2. contract unenforceable', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Issues Affecting Formation of Contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(418, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:44:41', '2016-05-30 18:44:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Duress', 'Where one party uses coercion which is subjectively great enough to overcome the free will of another, thereby inducing the other to enter or modify a contract, the contract or modification may be set aside.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. coercion great enough to â€œovercome the freewillâ€\n2. subjective standard of judgment', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Issues Affecting Formation of Contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(419, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:45:04', '2016-05-30 18:45:04', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Unconscionable Contract', 'An unconscionable contract is a contract with a provision that no fair and honest person would make and no person in his or her right mind would accept. Such contracts are usually agreed to through \\"oppression\\" in that the promisee knows that he or she is giving up his or her rights but is forced to if he or she wishes to purchase the subject product. Or, he or she is not aware of the rights that are being given up but through \\"unfair surprise\\" (such as small print or vagueness in terms) signs the contract anyway.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. no fair and honest person would make the provision or contract\n2. no person in right mind would accept the provision or contract\n3. results from oppression or unfair surprise', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Issues Affecting Formation of Contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(420, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:45:41', '2016-05-30 18:45:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Assignment', 'An assignment is a transfer of a contractual right. A contractual right is an intangible property and is called a â€œchose in action.â€ When a valid assignment has been made, the person receiving the transfer (the assignee) steps into the shoes of the person making the transfer (the assignor) and is now the proper party to enforce the contract.\nKey Words and Phrases:\n1. assignment is a transfer of a contractual right\n2. a contractual right is called a â€œchose in actionâ€\n3. the assignee \\"Steps into the Shoes\\" of the assignor', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(421, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:51:07', '2016-05-30 18:51:07', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Delegation and Assumption of Duties', 'A delegation and assumption of duties is a transfer of a contractual obligation. It involves a situation in which the assignor transfers his or her duty of performance to another. The person transferring the duty of performance is known as the delegator and the person who assumes the duty is known as the delegatee.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. delegation and assumption of duties is the transfer of a duty of performance\n2. the person transferring the duty is the delegator\n3. the person assuming the duty is the delegatee', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(422, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:51:25', '2016-05-30 18:51:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Third Party Beneficiary Contract', 'A third party beneficiary contract is a contract wherein performance by one party, the promisor, will confer a benefit upon a third party beneficiary, that is, a person or entity other than the promisee.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. a contract\n2. will confer benefit upon third person (or entity) other than the promisee', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(423, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:51:39', '2016-05-30 18:51:39', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Privity and Intent to Benefit', 'Under contract law, privity is required for a person to have standing to sue or enforce a contract. However, modernly, the privity requirement has been relaxed and a third party beneficiary can sue if he is an intended beneficiary.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. if third party is an intended beneficiary, privity not required', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(424, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 18:51:59', '2016-05-30 18:51:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Lawrence v. Fox', 'The landmark case of Lawrence v. Fox held that a third party beneficiary has the right to enforce the contract which will confer a benefit upon said third party.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. third party beneficiary has the right to enforce the contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(425, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:53:54', '2016-05-30 19:53:54', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Intended Beneficiary', 'An intended beneficiary is one in whose favor the original parties to the contract purposefully created an obligation. A third party must be an intended beneficiary in order to have standing to sue to enforce the provisions of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. one whose benefit was contemplated by the original parties to the contract\n2. must be an intended beneficiary to have standing to sue', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(426, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:55:24', '2016-05-30 19:55:24', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Creditor Beneficiary', 'A creditor beneficiary is an intended third party beneficiary who receives the benefit of a contract in satisfaction of an actual or supposed debt or obligation that existed between the third party beneficiary and the promisee to the contract. Modernly, a creditor beneficiary is typically called simply an â€œintended beneficiary.â€\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. creditor beneficiary receives the benefit of a contract\n2. promisee intends to satisfy a debt or obligation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(427, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:55:42', '2016-05-30 19:55:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Donee Beneficiary', 'A donee beneficiary is an intended third party beneficiary who receives the benefit of a contract as a gift from the promisee. Modernly, a donee beneficiary is typically called simply an â€œintended beneficiary.â€\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. donee beneficiary receives the benefit of a contract\n2. promisee intends to bestow a gift', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(428, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:56:04', '2016-05-30 19:56:04', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Incidental Beneficiary', 'An incidental beneficiary is one who may receive the benefit of the performance of the contractual provisions only incidentally and was not intended to receive the performance as a gift nor in satisfaction of a debt. An incidental beneficiary does not have standing to sue to enforce the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. one who receives the benefit of performance of a contract only incidentally\n2. does not have standing to sue', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(429, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:57:10', '2016-05-30 19:57:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Distinguishing Between Donee and Creditor Beneficiary', 'The reason for distinguishing between donee and creditor beneficiary is related to the rules of vesting. \n\nThe First Restatement of Contracts held that the donee\\''s rights vest upon the making of the contract, and that the creditor\\''s rights vest when he brings suit or otherwise materially changes his position in reliance upon the third party beneficiary contract. However, the majority rule today is that the rights of both the donee and the creditor beneficiary vest upon the beneficiary\\''s learning of the third party beneficiary contract and manifesting assent thereto. A minority rule holds that the rights of both the donee and creditor beneficiary vest upon the beneficiary materially changing his or her position in reliance upon the contract. \n\nTherefore, the original parties retain the power to defeat or alter the beneficiary\\''s rights up until the time that the beneficiary 1) materially changes his or her position including the bringing of a lawsuit or 2) manifests his or her assent to the contract after learning of its existence.\n\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. Under the First Restatement of Contracts, donee\\''s rights vest upon creation of the contract\n2. Under the First Restatement of Contracts, creditor\\''s rights vest when the creditor brings suit or otherwise materially changes position in reliance upon the contract\n3. Majority rule today: donee and the creditor beneficiariesâ€™ rights vest upon learning of the third party beneficiary contract\n4. original parties can defeat or alter rights until the beneficiary\na. manifests assent (majority rule) or\nb. detrimentally relies on the contract (minority rule)', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(430, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:57:40', '2016-05-30 19:57:40', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rights Against The Promisee', 'A third party donee beneficiary has no rights against the promisee by reason of the promisor\\''s failure to perform the contract. The \\"creditor\\" beneficiary, however, can sue the promisee on the original obligation since it remains unaffected by the third party beneficiary contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. donee beneficiary has no rights against the promisee\n2. creditor beneficiary can sue on the original obligation which remains unaffected by the third party beneficiary contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(431, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:57:57', '2016-05-30 19:57:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Rights against the Promisor', 'A third party intended beneficiary can sue the promisor for failure to perform the contract. The promisor can assert any defense against the third party beneficiary which could have been asserted against the promisee.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. intended beneficiary can sue promisor\n2. promisor may assert defenses against third party beneficiary that could have been asserted against promisee', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Third parties and contracts', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(432, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:58:32', '2016-05-30 19:58:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Covenant', 'In contract law, a covenant is a promise to act or to refrain from acting. It is not dependent upon the other partyâ€™s acts nor upon other events and, if the covenanting party breaches his covenant, the other party may bring an action for breach.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. promise to act or refrain from acting\n2. failure to keep the covenant constitutes a breach', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(433, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:58:50', '2016-05-30 19:58:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Warranty', 'A type of covenant in which one party attests to certain facts, for example, a warranty that a product will work, will work in a particular way, or that goods and services are as the seller represented them to be.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. promise related to an attestation of facts', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(434, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:59:20', '2016-05-30 19:59:20', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Express Warranties', 'Under the UCC, when a seller affirms a fact or makes a promise to the buyer which relates to the goods and becomes part of the basis of the bargain, the affirmation or promise creates an express warranty that the goods conform to the affirmation or promise. Additionally, a description of the goods which is made part of the basis of the bargain creates an express warranty that the goods conform to the description. Finally, a sample or model which is made part of the basis of the bargain creates an express warranty that the goods conform to the sample or model.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. affirmation of fact or promise related to the goods\n2. part of the basis upon which the other party agrees to the contract\n3. goods must conform to the affirmation or promise', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(435, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 19:59:48', '2016-05-30 19:59:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC Cumulation and Conflict of Warranties', 'Under the UCC, if reasonable, multiple warranties must be interpreted in a way such that the warranties are consistent and cumulative. If not reasonable, then the intention of the parties should determine the hierarchy of the warranties. The following rules govern such determination:\n1) exact or technical specifications displace an inconsistent sample or model or general language of description,\n2) a sample from an existing bulk displaces inconsistent general language of description, and\n3) express warranties displace inconsistent implied warranties other than an implied warranty of fitness for a particular purpose.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. multiple warranties to be interpreted such that they do not conflict, if reasonable', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(436, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:00:09', '2016-05-30 20:00:09', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Condition', 'A condition is an act or event which affects a duty to render a performance. A condition may be express or implied, and may be a condition precedent, a condition concurrent, or a condition subsequent.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. act or event (other than a lapse of time)\n2. affects a duty to render a promised performance', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(437, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:11:42', '2016-05-30 20:11:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Condition Precedent', 'A condition precedent is related to an event, other than a lapse of time, which must occur before a duty on the part of the defendant will arise. It may arise out of an express or implied term of the contract, or by operation of law under the Doctrine of Constructive Conditions.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. related to occurrence of an event\n2. event must occur before a duty on the part of the defendant will arise', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(438, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:11:55', '2016-05-30 20:11:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Condition Concurrent', 'A condition concurrent is a type of condition precedent which exists when the parties to a contract are bound to render performance at the same time.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. type of condition precedent\n2. parties must render performance at the same time', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(439, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:12:21', '2016-05-30 20:12:21', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Condition Subsequent', 'A condition subsequent is related to an event which, by\nagreement of the parties, operates to terminate a duty of performance after it has arisen.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. related to occurrence of an event\n2. by agreement of the parties\n3. occurrence of event terminates a duty of performance after it has arisen', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(440, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:12:37', '2016-05-30 20:12:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Express Condition', 'An express condition is stated in the contract and generally will be strictly and literally enforced by the courts.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. stated provision\n2. strictly and literally enforced', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(441, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:12:52', '2016-05-30 20:12:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Implied-in-Fact Condition', 'An implied-in-fact condition is one which is necessary to the performance of the contract between the parties and therefore is deemed to have been intended by the parties, but is not expressly stated.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. necessary to the performance of the contract\n2. not expressly stated', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(442, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:13:08', '2016-05-30 20:13:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Constructive Condition', 'A constructive condition is an implied-in-law condition, which the law will enforce even though the parties did not agree to it. Such conditions are implied by the law to promote justice.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. condition which the law will imply\n2. to promote justice', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(443, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:13:23', '2016-05-30 20:13:23', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Doctrine of Constructive Conditions', 'The Doctrine of Constructive Conditions holds that the fulfillment of a promise in a bilateral contract can be construed to be a condition of the other party\\''s performance even in the absence of an express provision to that effect.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. bilateral contract\n2. fulfillment of a promise is a condition of the other partyâ€™s performance', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(444, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:14:10', '2016-05-30 20:14:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Implied Condition of Cooperation', 'An implied condition of cooperation is implied in a contract whenever the cooperation of the promisee is necessary for the performance of the promise.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. condition of cooperation implied\n2. when cooperation of the promisee is necessary', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(445, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:14:26', '2016-05-30 20:14:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Satisfaction of Condition', 'In order to sue a defendant for failure to perform, the plaintiff must show that he has satisfied his own conditions or that his conditions are excused. A plaintiff satisfies a condition by complete performance, substantial performance (if it is a constructive condition), or by showing the contract is divisible.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. plaintiff must satisfy his own conditions in order to sue\n2. satisfaction is accomplished by:\na. complete performance\nb. substantial performance (constructive conditions only)\nc. divisibility of contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(446, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:14:52', '2016-05-30 20:14:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Substantial Performance', 'Under the Doctrine of Substantial Performance, a plaintiff who has failed to perform a constructive condition in a minor or immaterial respect may nevertheless recover on the contract. In order to recover, the plaintiff must prove: \n1) the defendant got substantially what he bargained for,\n2) the defendant can be reimbursed for what he did not receive,\n3) there will be a great hardship on the plaintiff if he is denied recovery under the contract, and\n4) the deviation was not willful.\n\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. applies to constructive condition only\n2. applies to plaintiff only\n3. plaintiff failed to perform a constructive condition in a minor or immaterial way and can prove:\na. the defendant got substantially what he bargained for,\nb. the defendant can be reimbursed for what he did not receive,\nc. great hardship on plaintiff if denied recovery, and\nd. deviation was not willful.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(447, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:15:22', '2016-05-30 20:15:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Divisible (or Severable) Contract', 'A divisible or severable contract is a bilateral contract in which the performance is divided into two or more separate units, either as to subject matter or time, and performance of each part by one party is the agreed exchange for a corresponding part by the other party. Some typical examples are construction contracts, contracts for the sale of goods and employment contracts.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. bilateral contract\n2. performance divided into two or more separate units', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(448, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:15:36', '2016-05-30 20:15:36', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Excuse of Condition', 'An excuse of condition occurs when the plaintiffâ€™s duty to perform is excused because the defendant has defaulted.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defendant fails to perform defendantâ€™s condition\n2. because of defendantâ€™s failure to perform, plaintiff does not perform\n3. plaintiffâ€™s performance is excused (never arises)', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(449, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:15:56', '2016-05-30 20:15:56', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Waiver of Condition', 'A waiver of condition results when a party to a contract voluntarily relinquishes his or her known right to assert the non-performance of a condition. A waiver can be given by express agreement or by conduct. A waiver may be retracted except where the other party has detrimentally relied on the waiver.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. voluntary relinquishment\n2. to assert known right to claim non-performance\n3. effected by express agreement or conduct', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(450, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:16:11', '2016-05-30 20:16:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Prospective Failure of Condition', 'A prospective failure of condition occurs when an anticipatory breach is present and will excuse the non-breaching party from his or her performance.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. anticipatory breach is present, and\n2. will excuse the non-breaching party\\''s performance', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(451, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:16:30', '2016-05-30 20:16:30', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Anticipatory Breach', 'An anticipatory breach occurs when one party to a contract makes it clear prior to the time performance is due that he or she will not perform. An anticipatory breach may be expressed in words or by action. The promisee may elect to sue immediately for damages or may wait until after performance has become due to then file suit.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unequivocal repudiation\n2. before performance is due\n3. promisee may sue immediately or after performance has become due', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(452, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:16:54', '2016-05-30 20:16:54', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Anticipatory Repudiation', 'An anticipatory repudiation is a form of anticipatory breach in which a party verbally and unequivocally repudiates a contract before performance has become due. \nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. anticipatory breach communicated by words', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(453, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:17:08', '2016-05-30 20:17:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Voluntary Disablement', 'A voluntary disablement is a form of anticipatory breach in which a partyâ€™s conduct makes it so that he cannot perform his own conditions.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. anticipatory breach communicated by actions', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(454, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:17:26', '2016-05-30 20:17:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Prevention', 'Prevention occurs when a party to a contract makes it impossible for the other party to perform.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. one party prevents the other party from performing', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(455, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:17:48', '2016-05-30 20:17:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Impossibility of Performance', 'A party to a contract will be released from an obligation to perform when, neither from his act nor from his neglect, and prior to being in default, it has become impossible for said party to perform.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. a party will be freed from an obligation to perform\n2. when neither from his act nor from his neglect, and\n3. prior to being in default\n4. it has become impossible for said party to perform', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(456, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:18:09', '2016-05-30 20:18:09', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Equitable Estoppel', 'Under the doctrine of equitable estoppel, a party who has taken unfair advantage of another, by using false statements or conduct to induce the other person to act or promise to act, is barred from asserting a failure of condition against that other person.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. one party takes advantage of the other through:\na. a false statement or false conduct\nb. intentionally or negligently made\nc. with intent to induce reliance\nd. where reasonable and detrimental reliance has occurred\n2. the innocent party is excused from performance', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Performance', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(457, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:18:41', '2016-05-30 20:18:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of Defendantâ€™s Duty to Perform', 'Once the plaintiff has either performed all his required conditions or has been excused from such performance, the defendantâ€™s duty to perform arises, unless the defendantâ€™s duty to perform is discharged.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. plaintiff performs or is excused from performance\n2. defendantâ€™s duty to perform arises or is discharged', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(458, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:21:14', '2016-05-30 20:21:14', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Merger', 'A merger is said to have occurred in a contractual situation when one contract supersedes or incorporates another.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. one contract supersedes or incorporates another', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(459, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:21:34', '2016-05-30 20:21:34', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Modification', 'A modification is a subsequent agreement entered into for consideration for purposes of modifying the prior contract. Since the Parol Evidence Rule only bars evidence related to agreements made prior to or concurrently with the written contract, the rule does not apply to modifications. Under the UCC, consideration is not required for a modification to be binding.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. a modification is a subsequent agreement\n2. it modifies the prior written contract\n3. the Parol Evidence issue does not apply to modifications\n4. under common law: consideration required\n5. under UCC: no consideration required', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(460, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 20:22:21', '2016-05-30 20:22:21', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mutual Rescission', 'A mutual rescission is an agreement by the parties to an existing executory contract to consider their contract null and void. This rescission is a contract in itself and requires mutual assent and consideration. The consideration for rescission is usually found in the fact that all parties incur a legal detriment by giving up their right to sue each other.\n\nIn a case involving an executed contract or a unilateral contract, an attempted rescission by mutual agreement would be lacking in consideration. Regarding an executed contract, the party who has received full performance is not giving up any right against the other, so he or she is incurring no legal detriment. Regarding a unilateral contract, the offeror only has the power to revoke the offer and terminate all obligations if revocation of the offer is communicated to the offeree before the offeree has materially changed his or her position in reliance upon the offer.\n\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. mutual agreement supported by consideration\n2. terminates contractual obligations of bilateral executory contracts', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(461, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:22:52', '2016-05-30 21:22:52', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Substitute Contract', 'A substitute contract is an agreement between the parties to a prior contract which takes the place of and discharges the prior contract. It differs from a novation in that no new parties are involved.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. new contract between the same parties\n2. replaces and discharges a prior contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(462, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:23:09', '2016-05-30 21:23:09', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Release', 'A release, at common law, was a complete discharge of existing contractual obligations given by one party to the contract to the other in a written document under seal. Modernly, in those jurisdictions that do not use the formal seal, a release is generally considered valid if supported by consideration.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. complete discharge of contractual obligation\n2. given (a) under seal or (b) by valid agreement supported by consideration', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(463, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:23:29', '2016-05-30 21:23:29', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Accord and Satisfaction', 'An accord is an agreement to compromise an existing obligation which has become the subject of a good faith dispute. Acceptance of the accord results in â€œsatisfaction,â€ meaning that the original obligation has been discharged with the accepting party no longer being able to charge the performing party with a breach of contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. an accord is an agreement to compromise a good faith dispute\n2. satisfaction is the acceptance of the compromise, which discharges the original obligation', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(464, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:23:51', '2016-05-30 21:23:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Novation', 'A novation is a new contract that is, in effect, an immediate discharge of a pre-existing contractual duty which creates a new duty in its place. It requires the replacement of one of the previously contracting parties with a new party who neither owed the previous duty nor was entitled to its performance.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. a new contact\n2. a pre-existing contractual duty owed by an outgoing party is immediately discharged in favor of a new contractual duty by an incoming party', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(465, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:24:10', '2016-05-30 21:24:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Frustration of Purpose', 'Although performance is still possible, a party to a contract will be discharged from an obligation to perform when an unanticipated event occurs after the formation of the contract, with a result that the partiesâ€™ main purpose in making the contract has become so frustrated that the benefit to be received by one party from the other party is now totally destroyed or materially impaired.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. conditions of performance will be discharged when:\na. bargained-for performance is still possible, but\nb. unanticipated event occurs after contract formation\nc. benefit to be received is totally destroyed or materially impaired', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(466, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:24:28', '2016-05-30 21:24:28', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Economic or Commercial Impracticability', 'Although performance is not totally impossible, a party to a contract will be discharged from an obligation to perform when an unanticipated difficulty has occurred after the formation of the contract, with the result that performance would be vastly different than that intended by the parties.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. conditions of performance will be discharged when:\na. unanticipated difficulty occurs after contract formation\nb. performance would be vastly different than intended', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(467, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:24:48', '2016-05-30 21:24:48', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Supervening Illegality', 'Supervening illegality occurs when, after the formation of the contract, the purpose for which the contract was created has become illegal. In such a case, the duty to perform is discharged.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. conditions of performance will be discharged when:\na. after formation of contract\nb. contractâ€™s purpose becomes illegal', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(468, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:27:08', '2016-05-30 21:27:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Failure of Consideration', 'Failure of consideration occurs when the subject matter of the consideration ceases to exist or becomes worthless even though valid consideration was present when the parties first contracted.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. conditions of performance will be discharged when:\na. consideration ceases to exist or becomes worthless\nb. valid consideration was present when parties first contracted', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Discharge of the Duty to Perform', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(469, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:27:37', '2016-05-30 21:27:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Failure of Condition', 'Failure of condition occurs when one party fails to perform his condition, resulting in a breach of contract. The non-breaching partyâ€™s own duty of performance is discharged. This means the contract is still in effect and the breaching party still has a duty to perform. If he does not, contract remedies may be imposed.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. failure to perform a condition is a breach\n2. contract is still in effect, meaning remedies are available for the breach', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(470, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:27:51', '2016-05-30 21:27:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Breach of Contract', 'A breach of contract occurs when one party to a contract fails to perform pursuant to the terms of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. one party to a contract fails to perform', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(471, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:28:10', '2016-05-30 21:28:10', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Material Breach', 'A breach is material if it is so substantial that it defeats the purpose of the parties in making the contract or if it is so significant as to destroy the value of the contract. Whether a breach is material is a question of fact. If a breach is material, the plaintiff is justified in treating the entire transaction as ended and may thereafter sue for damages.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. defeats purpose or destroys value of the contract\n2. ends the transaction and the plaintiff may sue for damages', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(472, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:29:32', '2016-05-30 21:29:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Minor Breach', 'If a breach is minor in nature the plaintiff has a cause of action for damages caused by the breach, but the contract remains in effect.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. there is still value to the contract\n2. contract remains in effect, but plaintiff may sue for damages caused by the breach', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(473, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:30:57', '2016-05-30 21:30:57', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Breach by Tendering Non-conforming Goods', 'Under the UCC, a delivery of non-conforming goods is a breach unless the goods are accompanied by a notification that the goods are being offered as an accommodation, in which case the tender is a counter offer.\n\nIf non-conforming goods are delivered as part of an installment contract, the buyer may reject the shipment, but the rest of the contract (additional installments) remains in effect. However, if the non-conformity substantially impairs the value of the whole contract, then the whole contract is breached.\n\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. tender of non-conforming goods is a breach unless buyer is notified that they are an accommodation\n2. installment contracts:\na. a non-conforming shipment may be rejected\nb. not a breach of the whole contract unless the value of the whole is substantially impaired', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(475, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:35:42', '2016-05-30 21:35:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Cure', 'Under the UCC, if non-conforming goods are tendered and rejected, the seller may notify the buyer that he intends to rectify the problem as long as the time for performance has not passed.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. Under the UCC, the seller may cure non-conforming goods prior to law day', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Breach', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(476, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:36:08', '2016-05-30 21:36:08', 1, NULL, NULL, 'General Damages', 'In contract law, general damages are those which are the direct, natural, or probable losses caused by a breach. Included would be damages such as the difference between contract and market prices, the difference between the value of the goods as delivered and as warranted, and interest on money that has been wrongfully withheld.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. direct, natural or probable losses', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(477, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:37:42', '2016-05-30 21:37:42', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Special Damages', 'In contract law, special damages are those which are unique to an individual case and thus, must be specially pleaded and proved. Special damages are recoverable when special circumstances exist which cause some unusual injury to the plaintiff and when the defendant knew or should have known of the special circumstances at the time the defendant entered into the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. unique to individual case\n2. must be specially pleaded and proved\n3. defendant knew or should have foreseen the loss at time of creation of contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(478, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:38:07', '2016-05-30 21:38:07', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Consequential Damages', 'Consequential damages are special damages. However, this term reflects the \\"foreseeability\\" requirement that arose out of the case of Hadley v. Baxendale years ago in England. It was held in this case that compensation in a breach of contract case should be given only for those injuries that the defendant, at the time the contract was made, had reason to foresee as the probable result of his or her breach. Damages that are unforeseeable will be held too remote and, therefore, uncollectible.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. same as special damages\n2. must be foreseeable at time of creation of contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL);
INSERT INTO `records_lawcourse` (`id`, `uid`, `created`, `updated`, `status`, `lat`, `lng`, `title`, `description`, `details`, `path`, `deleted`, `users_info_id`, `location_id`, `admin_approved`, `i1`, `i2`, `i3`, `i4`, `d1`, `d2`, `d3`, `d4`, `vc1`, `vc2`, `vc3`, `vc4`, `t1`, `t2`, `t3`, `t4`, `parent_id`, `reference_id`, `expiry_dt`) VALUES
(479, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:38:23', '2016-05-30 21:38:23', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Compensatory Damages', 'Compensatory damages include both general and special damages, and are awarded to the non-breaching party to place that party in the same position that he or she would have been in, had the contract been performed as agreed.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. awarded to place non-breaching party into the same position he or she would have been in, had the contract been performed', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(480, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:39:16', '2016-05-30 21:39:16', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Expectancy Measure of Compensatory Damages (Expectation Damages)', 'Where possible, the court will award compensatory damages according to the calculation of what the plaintiff expected to receive from performance of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. what the plaintiff expected to receive from performance of the contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(481, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:39:33', '2016-05-30 21:39:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Reliance Measure of Compensatory Damages (Reliance Damages)', 'When the expectancy cannot be calculated to a reasonable certainty, then the court may award damages according to the calculation of what the plaintiff expended in reliance on the contract. Essential reliance damages are expenses incurred in the performance or preparation for performance of a contract and need not be foreseeable. Incidental reliance damages are foreseeable expenses incurred because of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. what the plaintiff spent in reliance on the contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(482, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:39:55', '2016-05-30 21:39:55', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Liquidated Damages', 'Liquidated damages are an amount of damages stated in a contract in advance of any breach. If there is a valid liquidated damages clause in a contract, it will be the sole remedy available upon a breach of the contract. In order for such a clause to be found valid, it must be shown that it is based on anticipated damages as opposed to being a mere penalty. This is shown through establishing that damages would have been difficult to ascertain at the time the contract was made, and the amount set as liquidated damages is a reasonable forecast of what damages would be.\r\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\r\n1. agreed to in a contract\r\n2. sole remedy where valid\r\n3. must not be punitive, as proved by showing:\r\na. damages would have been difficult to ascertain at creation of contract\r\nb. amount is a reasonable forecast of damages', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(483, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:40:41', '2016-05-30 21:40:41', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Nominal Damages', 'Nominal damages are given by the court to a non-breaching party who has suffered no damages or who has been unable to prove damages at trial, but who nevertheless has been wronged and is entitled to a judgment for technical breach of contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. aggrieved party cannot prove damages or has suffered no damages', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(484, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:41:33', '2016-05-30 21:41:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Punitive or Exemplary Damages', 'Punitive damages, which are also called Exemplary Damages, are damages that are granted to a plaintiff to punish the defendant for malicious, wanton or willful conduct and are awarded to make an \\"example\\" of the defendant\\''s conduct; so that such conduct will not be repeated again. Punitive or exemplary damages are not typically allowable for breach of contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. punishment for malicious or wanton or willful conduct\n2. generally not awarded for breach of contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(485, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:41:46', '2016-05-30 21:41:46', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mitigation of Damages', 'Mitigation of damages refers to efforts of the non-breaching party to use ordinary care to mitigate, or limit, the damages caused by the other party\\''s breach.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. efforts to limit the harm caused by a breach of contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(486, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:42:06', '2016-05-30 21:42:06', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Doctrine of Avoidable Consequences', 'Under the Doctrine of Avoidable Consequences, the plaintiff must use ordinary care to mitigate his damages. If the defendant can show that the plaintiff failed to mitigate damages, the plaintiffâ€™s recovery may be reduced.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. plaintiff must make reasonable effort to mitigate\n2. damages may be reduced for plaintiffâ€™s failure to mitigate', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(487, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:42:32', '2016-05-30 21:42:32', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Legal vs. Equitable Remedies', 'An equitable remedy will only be awarded if the available legal remedies are inadequate. Legal remedies may be inadequate for many reasons, including situations in which the dollar damages are too small or too speculative; continuing or multiple suits are possible; a threatened injury may be irreparable; or real property (which is always unique) or a unique chattel is involved.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. equitable remedy is allowed only if legal remedies are inadequate', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(488, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:42:59', '2016-05-30 21:42:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Quasi Contract', 'Quasi contract is an equitable remedy which allows the plaintiff to recover a benefit that was conferred upon the defendant despite the absence of a contract, usually because of a special relationship between the parties, conduct by the parties, or because the defendant would be unjustly enriched if he or she were allowed to retain the benefit.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. remedy to prevent unjust enrichment\n2. no contract exists', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(489, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:43:11', '2016-05-30 21:43:11', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Quantum Meruit', 'Quantum Meruit refers to the reasonable value deserved for one\\''s labor, and is awarded in a quasi-contract claim.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. reasonable value for services\n2. quasi-contractual recovery', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(490, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:43:26', '2016-05-30 21:43:26', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Quantum Valebant', 'Quantum Valebant refers to reasonable value that is deserved as payment for goods, and is awarded in a quasi-contract claim.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. reasonable value of goods\n2. quasi-contractual recovery', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(491, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 21:43:47', '2016-05-30 21:43:47', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Equitable Rescission or Cancellation', 'Rescission is an equitable remedy which prevents unjust enrichment by cancelling the contract and restoring the parties to their pre-contractual positions for such reasons as fraud, undue influence, duress, mistake, or substantial breach.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. equitable remedy\n2. restores to pre-contract position', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(492, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:55:25', '2016-05-30 22:55:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Restitution', 'Restitution may be awarded as either a legal or equitable remedy, to prevent unjust enrichment to the defendant. Restitutionary damages are calculated by determining the value that the defendant received from the plaintiffâ€™s performance of the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. legal or equitable remedy\n2. goal is to prevent unjust enrichment to the defendant\n3. determined according to value received by the defendant', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(493, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:55:45', '2016-05-30 22:55:45', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Reformation', 'Reformation is an equitable remedy in which the court modifies a written contract to reflect the actual intent of the parties in a situation where the contract is not an accurate representation of the partiesâ€™ agreement. It is most often used to correct a contract in cases involving fraud or mutual mistake.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. equitable remedy\n2. court â€œcorrectsâ€ a contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(494, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:55:58', '2016-05-30 22:55:58', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Injunction', 'An injunction is an equitable remedy in which a court issues an order commanding or preventing an action.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. equitable remedy\n2. court commands or prohibits an action', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(495, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:56:31', '2016-05-30 22:56:31', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Specific Performance', 'Specific Performance is an equitable remedy in the form of a mandatory decree or injunction which orders a contracting party to perform that which he has promised to perform under the contract.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. equitable remedy\n2. court orders a party to perform as required by the terms of the contract', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(496, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:56:54', '2016-05-30 22:56:54', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC: Buyerâ€™s Remedies Prior to Acceptance of Goods', 'Under the UCC, if non-conforming goods are delivered to the buyer, the buyer has several options, including holding the goods as a security for damages, canceling the contract, recovering payments already made, or suing for damages or specific performance. However, the buyer must use reasonable care in holding the goods.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. buyer may hold non-conforming goods as security\n2. buyer may cancel the contract if non-conforming goods are shipped\n3. buyer may recover payments made for non-conforming goods\n4. buyer may sue for damages caused by shipment of non-conforming goods\n5. buyer may sue for specific performance if contracted goods are unique\n6. buyer must hold sellerâ€™s non-conforming goods with reasonable care', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(497, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:58:14', '2016-05-30 22:58:14', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC: Buyerâ€™s Remedies After Acceptance of Goods', 'Under the UCC, if the buyer accepts a shipment of non-conforming goods, the buyer must pay the contract price but may subtract the difference between the value of the accepted goods and the value of the goods if they had conformed, plus incidental and consequential costs, but minus\nexpenses saved by the sellerâ€™s breach. The buyer must notify the seller of any deduction in contract price.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. If buyer accepts non-conforming goods, payment is calculated as:\na. contract price, minus difference between value of the goods as shipped vs. as promised\nb. plus incidental and consequential costs incurred by buyer due to sellerâ€™s breach\nc. minus costs saved by sellerâ€™s breach\n2. buyer must notify seller of price deduction', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(498, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:58:51', '2016-05-30 22:58:51', 1, NULL, NULL, 'UCC: Seller\\''s Remedies Prior to Buyer\\''s Acceptance of Goods', 'Under the UCC, if the buyer breaches the contract before the buyer has accepted the sellerâ€™s goods, the seller can cancel contract; withhold delivery; stop shipment of goods which are already in transit; or, if the goods are unfinished, the seller may stop production and sell the materials as scrap or finish production and resell the goods. In any of these situations, the seller can also sue for damages caused by the breach.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. If buyer breaches prior to acceptance of goods, seller may:\na. cancel the contract,\nb. withhold delivery,\nc. stop shipment,\nd. finish goods and resell, or\ne. stop production and sell as scrap.\n2. Seller can recover damages from buyer:\na. where resale cannot be accomplished, seller recovers contract price,\nb. where resale is accomplished, seller recovers the difference between resale price and contract price, plus incidental damages, but minus expenses saved by buyer\\''s breach\nc. where market price has dropped, seller can recover the difference between the contract and market prices, plus incidental damages', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(499, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:59:17', '2016-05-30 22:59:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Lost Volume Seller', 'A lost volume seller is a seller who does not recover the profit lost by a buyerâ€™s breach via reselling the goods because the seller would have made the second sale anyway. Such a situation occurs when the seller has an unlimited or large enough supply of goods that he or she can make repeated sales.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. seller could made additional sales whether or not buyer breached', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(500, '112913147917981568678', '2016-05-30 22:59:33', '2016-05-30 22:59:33', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Seller\\''s Remedies after Buyer\\''s Acceptance of Goods', 'Under the UCC, if a buyer has already accepted the sellerâ€™s goods and then breaches the contract, the seller may recover the goods or sue for the contract price.\nKEY WORDS AND PHRASES:\n1. seller can recover goods\n2. seller can sue for contract price, plus incidental damages', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Remedies', 'Clancey\\''s Outlaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(501, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 15:49:01', '2016-06-04 15:49:01', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Actus Reus', '1. Definition: A voluntary act that causes social harm. \n2. Actus reus is satisfied by either: \n  A. A volitional act \n    i. Thoughts alone are insufficient to establish the actus reus element. \n      a. Some kind of action in addition to thoughts is required for a valid criminal prosecution. \n      b. A legislature cannot criminalize thoughts that it disagrees with. \n      c. Thoughts plus an overt act or substantial step toward a crime can constitute an attempt crime; historically, attempt crimes were treated as misdemeanors; however, modernly, attempt crimes are classified as felonies. \n    ii. Once an act is established, thoughts an be used by the prosecution as evidence of motive or intent. \n      a. EX: The punishment for a battery offense can be enhanced because of the defendant\\''s biased motive of selecting the victim on account of the victim\\''s race. \n  B. An omission to act where there is a legal duty to act', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ACT', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(502, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 15:51:00', '2016-06-04 15:51:00', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Volition', 'The act of willing, choosing, or resolving; exercise of willing: She left of her own volition. a choice or decision made by the will.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(503, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 15:51:20', '2016-06-04 15:51:20', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Misdemeanors', 'A minor crime, punishable by a fine or a light jail term. Common misdemeanors, such as traffic violations, are usually dealt with informally, without a trial. (Compare felony.)', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(504, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 16:17:05', '2016-06-04 16:17:05', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Omission', '1. Legal duty to act created by:\n  A. Statute\n    i. EX: Good Samaritan statutes mandate a duty to assist if one can assist without causing danger or peril to any person; violation of a Good Samaritan statue typically consitutes a misdemeanor offense with a fine as punishment.\n  B. Contract\n    i. EX: A contract with a nursing home or private party to provide care; failure to provide the food and medical care that was contractually agreed on can establish the actus reus element necessary to prosecute the caregiver whose omission to act caused the death of a patient.\n  C. Voluntary assumption of care and seclusion.\n  D. Special relationship\n    ii. EX: A parent-child relationship creates a duty to provide food, shelter, and protection for the child; a parent\\''s failure to protect a child from physical abuse can establish the actus reus element necessary to prosecute the parent, even if the parent did not do any of the physical abuse, based on the parent\\''s omission to affirmatively act to protect the child.\n    iii. EX: A stranger does not have a duty to protect a child from physical abuse unless specifically required by a state statute.\n  E. Wrongful creation of peril.\n\n2. Note: Failure to act where there is no duty to act does not create criminal liability.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ACT', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(505, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 16:17:38', '2016-06-04 16:17:38', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Statute', 'An act of a legislature that declares, proscribes, or commands something; a specific law, expressed in writing. A statute is a written law passed by a legislature on the state or federal level. Statutes set forth general propositions of law that courts apply to specific situations.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(506, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 16:17:50', '2016-06-04 16:17:50', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Seclusion', 'Seclusion is the act of secluding, i.e. shutting out or keeping apart from society, or the state of being secluded, or a place that facilitates it (a secluded place). A person, a couple, or a larger group may go to a secluded place for privacy, or because the place is quiet.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(507, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 16:18:04', '2016-06-04 16:18:04', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Peril', 'Serious and immediate danger.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(508, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 17:07:17', '2016-06-04 17:07:17', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Voluntariness of Acts', '1. Defenses to the actus reus element.\n  A. Involuntary\n    i. EX: Individual is drunk inside a private home and the police come into the home and forcibly carry the individual out to the street and charge the individual with drunkenness in public; the defense of involuntariness is valid.\n  B. Reflexive\n  C. Unconscious\n    i. EX: One who become unconscious and causes harm due to a sudden unexpected medical condition will have a valid defense that his/her act was involuntary and does not satisfy the requisite actus reus element, making the harm caused noncriminal; a sudden seizure, heart attack, stroke, or other disabling attack would qualify in this category.\n    ii. EX: However, when an individual becomes unconscious due to a known medical condition, the involuntary defense may be invalid, as the disregard of the known risk of the possible unconsciousness negates the concept of the unconsciousness being involuntary; an epileptic with a known history of seizures who takes the risk of driving, becomes unconscious, and causes harm would not have the benefit of the involuntary defense.\n    iii. EX: Unconsciousness due to voluntary intoxication is not a valid defense that the act that cuased harm was involuntary; a drunk driver who becomes unconscious behind the wheel of a car cannot benefit from the involuntary defense and is still criminally responsible for the harm caused by the reckless disregard of the consequences of the act of driving while intoxicated.\n  D. Involuntarily intoxicated\n  E. Asleep (i.e., sleep walking)\n  F. Convulsive (i.e. epilepsy)\n  G. Note: Not every act in the criminal transaction must be voluntary, but the crime must include a voluntary act to satisfy actus reus.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ACT', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(509, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 17:41:22', '2016-06-04 17:41:22', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Specific Intent', '1. Common law jurisdictions draw a distinction between specific and general intent crimes; Model Penal Code (MPC) jurisdiction do not.\n2. Requirements\n  A. Requires the doing of an act and doing it with specific intent to cause the social harm.\n    i. Must have the general intent to do the act.\n    ii. Must have the specific intent to achieve the consequences of the crime, and\n    iii. The actus reus and the specific intent must occur at the same time.\n      a. EX: The requisite mens rea for 1st degree murder requires proof of a \\"specific intent to kill\\" (premeditated and deliberate killing of a human being), weighing the consequences, and specifically intending death.\n3. Defenses to specific intent\n  A. Voluntary intoxication is allowed in most states as a defense to a specific intent crime wherein the defendant\\''s intoxication prevented the formation of the requisite specific intent needed to commit the crime (i.e., unable to intend the consequences of his/her actions); however, although voluntary intoxication may work to defend against a specific intent crime, it might not negate all criminal liability and other related general intent crimes could be validly charged.\n    i. EX: If a defendant asserts voluntary intoxication to defend against the specific intent element of premeditation and deliberation in a 1st degree murder charge, a voluntary intoxication defense may not protect the same defendant against the lesser offense of 2nd degree murder that requires only general intent.\n    ii. Voluntary intoxication defenses are generally disfavored.\n    iii. States are not required to recognize the defense of voluntary intoxication, and it is constitutionally valid to instead ban the defense of voluntary intoxication, and it is constitutionally valid to instead ban the defense of voluntary intoxication entirely, which some states have done.\n  B. Involuntary intoxication is accepted as a vlid defense to mens rea.\n  C. Mistake of fact, even if the mistake is unreasonable if in good faith.\n  D. Mistake of law, a small category of criminal statues that require, as an element of the crime, proof that the defendant knew the law prior to violating it. (i.e., the defendant acted with knowledge that his conduct was unlawful).\n    i. Knowledge of law element found only in complex criminal codes (tax code, immigration law, regulatory laws, etc).\n    ii. Even if it is unreasonable that defendant did not know the law, the defense can work if defendant was acting in good faith.\n4. Examples of common law specific intent crimes.\n  A. 1st degree murder (premeditated and deliberate)\n  B. Attempt\n  C. Solicitation\n  D. Conspiracy\n  E. Assault\n  F. Robbery and Larceny\n    i. Proof of â€œconditionalâ€ intent to harm satisfies statutory requirement.\n  G. Forgery\n  H. False pretenses\n    i. Statutory language must include â€œintent to defraud\\"\n  I. Embezzlement.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intent (Mens Rea)', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(510, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 21:41:37', '2016-06-04 21:41:37', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Voluntary Intoxication', 'Voluntary Intoxication means intoxicating oneself with knowledge of getting impaired. Usually, voluntary intoxication is done by the intake of any alcohol or drug. In voluntary intoxication the person consuming the intoxicated drug will be in a position that s/he will be physically or mentally impaired.\n\nAlthough, voluntary intoxication is not considered as a defense to a general intent crime, there are certain defenses that a person can claim even if s/he is intoxicated.. They are:\n\n1. defense of Mens Rea;\n\n2. special rule of homicide;\n\n3. voluntary act; and\n\n4. intoxicated-induced insanity.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(511, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-04 22:28:13', '2016-06-04 22:28:13', 1, NULL, NULL, 'General Intent', '1. Requirements\n  A. All crimes require general intent.\n  B. The general intent must occur at the same time as the actus reus.\n\n2. Defenses\n  A. Mistake of fact must be honest and reasonable but cannot be a legal or moral wrong.\n    i. Legal wrong-moral wrong exception: Assuming the reasonable mistake, if the defendantâ€™s act would still be illegal or immoral, the mistake of fact defense is invalid because the defendant knew he was committing a wrong, just a different wrong the defendant knew he was committing a wrong, just a different wrong.\n  B. Involuntary intoxication is a defense, but voluntary intoxication is not a defense.\n\n3. Examples of common law general intent crimes\n  A. Rape\n  B. Battery\n  C. Involuntary manslaughter\n\n4. Transferred intent\n  A. When the defendant intends a harmful result to Victim A and, in trying to carry out that intent, causes a harmful result to Victim B.\n    i. Some courts apply transferred apply transferred intent both to a completed crime and to an attempted crime.\n      a. EX: Defendant A may be convicted of attempted murder of intended Victim B, who was not hit, and intentional murder of unintended Victim C.\n      b. EX: Transferred intent also applied to affirm the 1st degree convictions where both the unintended victim and intended were killed.\n    ii. Some courts do not apply transferred intent to attempted crimes\n      a. EX: If Defendant A shoots to kill Victim B, wounding B and Victim C, Defendant A may be charged with attempted murder of B but not C.\n\n5. Model Penal Code (MPC)\n  A. MPC does not distinguish between specific intent and general intent crimes.\n  B. Intoxication\n    i. Under MPC, any intoxication is a defense if it negates the mens rea of the crime.\n    ii. However, if it is a crime of recklessness, a defendantâ€™s intoxication is immaterial and unawareness of the risk due to voluntary intoxication will not negate mens rea.\n    iii. Involuntary and pathological intoxication can be affirmative defenses if intoxication-caused loss of mental capacity was equivalent to temporary insanity.\n  C. Ignorance or mistake: A mistake is a defense if it negates the mens rea.\n    i. Legal wrong doctrine is still applied.\n      a. Mistake of fact defense is not available if, assuming defendantâ€™s mistake, he/she would have been guilty of another offense.\n      b. May reduce sentence to lesser mistaken crime.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Intent (Mens Rea)', 'Quick Study Criminal Law', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(512, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 12:35:02', '2016-06-18 12:35:02', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Malum In Se', 'Malum  in  se  refers  to  a  wrong  in  itself,  in  other  words,  something  naturally  evil.\nExamples are:\n1. Burglary\n2. Robbery\n3. Arson\n4. Rape\n5. Manslaughter\n6. Murder', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(513, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 12:38:43', '2016-06-18 12:38:43', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Malum Prohibitum', 'An act that is not inherently immoral, but is expressly forbidden by positive law.\n\nCrimes by legislative Statues\nViolation of Statues\n\nExamples:\nSelling liquor to minor\nSpeeding\nRunning a stop sign', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(514, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 12:43:27', '2016-06-18 12:43:27', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Infamous Crimes', 'Crime that is shameful or disgraceful.\nUsually involves fraud or dishonesty.\n\nExamples:\nPerjury\nEmbezzlement\nMail and Securities Fraud', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(515, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:01:03', '2016-06-18 13:01:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Felonies', 'Crimes that are generally punishable by death or imprisonment exceeding one year.\n\nExamples are:\n1.  Burglary\n2.  Robbery\n3.  Arson\n4.  Rape\n5.  Manslaughter\n6.  Murder\n7. Mayhem', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(516, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:04:18', '2016-06-18 13:04:18', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Misdemeanors', 'Offenses lower than felonies, and generally punishable by less than a year or fine.\n\nExamples are:\nDepending on the jurisdiction, examples of misdemeanors may include: petty theft, prostitution, public intoxication, simple assault, disorderly conduct, trespass, vandalism, reckless driving, discharging a firearm within city limits, possession of cannabis and in some jurisdictions first-time possession of certain other drugs, and other similar crimes.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(517, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:10:18', '2016-06-18 13:10:18', 1, NULL, NULL, '5 Basic Elements of Crime', '5 Basic Elements of Crime are:\n1. Actus Reus\n2. Mens Rea\n3. Concurrence\n4. Causation\n5. Resulting Injury or Crime', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(518, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:13:25', '2016-06-18 13:13:25', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Actus Reus', 'A guilty act that is conscious and voluntary.\n\nNo voluntary example is that someone who is driving a car with no history of illness got stroke and he hit somebody on sidewalk, so he is not guilty of his actions because it is not voluntary.\nAnother example is of crime in sleep walking, they are not in their control.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(519, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:19:03', '2016-06-18 13:19:03', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Omission To Act', 'No duty to action on behalf of a stranger in peril.\n\nExceptions: There are some duties to act which are prescribed by law. For example you have duty to pay taxes, if you don\\''t pay taxes, you will be liable for omission to act. Another one is security guard at pool and he has duty to save people in pool and if some one is drowning, he has to save him and if he flirts with girls and some one dies then he has done omission to act. We can have him guilty of involuntary manslaughter for him to failure to act. Another example is relationships: husband and wife can aid to each other, parents and child can aid to each other, employee and employer can aid to each other.\n\nSo duties to act work in by contract, by law, by relationships.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(520, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:42:17', '2016-06-18 13:42:17', 1, NULL, NULL, '6 Step Approach to Evidence', 'Youtube Link: \nhttp://uk.youtube.com/watch?v=Wq09x73-mBc&feature=channel_page\n\n*Follow Federal Evidence Rules of Law\n\n1. What type of Case is at issue?\n            a. Criminal Case\n            b. Civil Case\n2. Where in the trial process are we?\na. Pre-lim hearing\n            b. Grand jury hearing\n            c. Direct examination\n            d. Cross examination\n            e. Re-direct\n3. Who is on the witness stand testifying?\n            a. Plaintiff\n            b. Defendant\n            c. Actual witness to crime or accident\n            d. Expert witness\n4. What TYPE of evidence is at issue?\n            a. Sensory\n                        1. Sightâ€¦what someone saw\n                        2. Soundâ€¦what someone heard/said\n                        3. Scentâ€¦ what someone smelled\n                        4. Tasteâ€¦what someone tasted\n                        5. Touchâ€¦what someone felt\n            b. Physical Evidence\nBook of authority, business docs, notes, photo, gun, knife, drugs ECTâ€¦\n            c. Character evidence\n                        1. Specific act\n                        2. Opinion\n\n5. Find the Hearsay Exception or Exemption!\nRemember there is a difference between the two and they eat up the general rule!\n\n6. Is it Relevant or have Probative value?', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(521, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:43:39', '2016-06-18 13:43:39', 1, NULL, NULL, '6 Step Approach to Contracts', 'Youtube Link:\nhttp://uk.youtube.com/watch?v=bqfkgk3MiZM&feature=channel\n\n*Follow common law for services and UCC for sale of goods!\n\n1. Narrow your focus on whatâ€™s important in the fact pattern. â€œThe golden nuggetsâ€\n\n            a. Dates (create a time line)\n            b. Dollar amounts ($500 UCC-sales of goods)\n            c. Words of Offer, Acceptance, Rejection, Consideration and Conditions\n\n2. Is the contract for services or goods?\na. Services are controlled by common law\nb. Goods over $500 by UCC\n\n3. Is it in Writing or Verbal?\nContracts that must be in writing are marriage, one year to complete, sales of goods over $500, sales of real estate\n\n4. Who are the contracting parties?\n            a. Merchants\n            b. Non-Merchants\n\nKnow the special rules that apply to merchants under the UCC\n\n5. Are there any third party rights?\n\n6. What are the possible defenses?', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(522, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:44:44', '2016-06-18 13:44:44', 1, NULL, NULL, '3 Step Approach to Constitutional Law', 'Youtube Link:\nhttp://uk.youtube.com/watch?v=lUM20gUQ3_8&feature=channel_page\n\n*Follow Federal Constitution Law\n\n1.THE WHAT\nWhat level of government is trying to pass or enforce a law?  5 levels to be aware of areâ€¦\n            1. City\n            2. State\n            Federal branch has 3\n                        3. Congress\n                        4. Executive (The President)\n                        5. Judicial (The Supreme Court)\n\nAsk yourself, do they have the power to enforce this law or are they usurping another governmental entities power? And, what part of the Constitution gives them power?\n\n2. THE WHO\nWho are they trying to pass of enforce the law against?\n            a. One government over another?\n            b. Government over religion/church/group?\nWhat is their scrutiny level?\n            c.  Government over individual rights?\nAre fundamental rights at issue?\nDo they have Standing?\n\n3. THE WHY\nWhy are they REALLY trying to pass or enforce THIS law?\nIs their reason Constitutional?\nIs the issue a moot point?', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(523, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:45:50', '2016-06-18 13:45:50', 1, NULL, NULL, '6 Step Approach to Torts', '*Follow Restatement of Torts, unless they tell you otherwise or give a statute to use.\n\nApproaches to crimes and torts are very much alike! They are driven by specific words and terms that show â€INTENTâ€ and â€œKNOWLEDGEâ€ to commit a crime or do and act that results in harm to another. The â€œgolden nuggetsâ€ are words of knowledge, mental state, and actions, because, they will direct you to the correct answer.\n\n*Remember intent in torts is base on intent to do the act that caused the resulting harm. NOT intent to cause harm that results.\n\n1. Focus on verbs, action words that describe what the defendant did. Examples are Shot, hit, push, stabbed, ran, jumped, drove, robbed, hid, stole, pulled, pushed, dragged, attacked, moved, threw, tossed, grabbed,\n\n2. Focus on adjectives, descriptive words that give rise to the mental state of the defendant. Examples of mental state are angry, enraged, sad, decided, thought, depressed, in control, happy, distraught, elated, insane, crazy, dissolution, out of control, under the influence, drunk, mad.\n\n3. Focus on words that tell us what the defendant knew or agreed to. Examples are heard, said, told, agreed, discussed, over heard, saw, looked at, decided, knew, knowingly, intentionally, thought, mindful, expressed.\n\n4. Who are the parties?\na. Who did what to whom and why? Think about possible defenses!\n\n5. What are the possible tort actions?\n            a. Intentional\n            b. Negligence\n            c. Defamation\n\n6. Are all elements of the tort complete and satisfied?', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, NULL),
(524, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:46:29', '2016-06-18 13:46:29', 1, NULL, NULL, '4 Step Approach to Real Property', 'In property, the answer choices will automatically tell you what area of property law the question is asking about. And, just like contracts you must focus on DATES, DOLLAR AMOUNTS AND WHO THE PARTIES ARE!\n\n1. Narrow your focus on whatâ€™s important in the fact pattern. â€œThe golden nuggetsâ€\n\nIn addition to dates, dollar amount and who the parties are, look for legal terms! Property is driven by the legal terms in the fact patterns. They will lead you to the correct answer choice.\n\n2. What type of property right/interest is at issue?\n\n            a. Ownership types\nFee simple, Fee tail, Life estate\n`            b. Future interests\nReversion, possible reverter, right of re-entry, remainders, executory interests\n            c. Landlord/tenant aka Non-freehold estates\n                        Estate for years, periodic tenancy, tenancy at will, tenancy at sufferance\n            d. Non-possessory\nEasements, profit, license, covenants, equitable servitude\n            e. Conveyances\n                        Sales of land, deed delivery, recording acts, mortgages\n            f. Concurrent estates\n                        Tenants in common, joint tenancy, tenancy by the entirety\n\n3. Follow the given statutes to a â€œTâ€\n\n4. Is there a written contract or is it only verbal?', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, NULL),
(525, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 13:47:04', '2016-06-18 13:47:04', 1, NULL, NULL, '6 Step Approach to Criminal Law', '*Follow the MAJORITY! Which is often common law! Except in Burglary ONLY follow common law UNLESS they ask specifically for MPC or give a statute to use.\n\n1. Focus on verbs, action words that describe what the defendant did.\n\nExamples are Shot, hit, push, stabbed, ran, jumped, drove, robbed, hid, stole, pulled, pushed, dragged, attacked, moved, threw, tossed, grabbed,\n\n2. Focus on adjectives, descriptive words that give rise to the mental state of the defendant.\n\nExample of mental state are angry, enraged, sad, depressed, in control, happy, distraught, elated, insane, dissolution, out of control, under the influence, drunk, crazy, mad.\n\n3. Focus on words that tell you what the defendant knew or agreed to.\n\nExamples are heard, said, told, agreed, discussed, over heard, saw, look at, knew, knowingly, agreed, thought, mindful, expressed,\n\n4. What are the possible crimes?\n            a. Homicide\n            b. Theft Crimes\n            c. Crimes against habitation\n            d. Crimes against people\n            e. SAC Solicitation, Attempt, Conspiracy\n                       \n5. Are all elements of the crime complete and satisfied?\n\n6. What are the possible defenses?', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(526, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 15:27:02', '2016-06-18 15:27:02', 1, NULL, NULL, 'The Corpus Delicti', 'The fact of a crime having been actually committed.\n\nCorpus delicti is a term referring to the principle that a crime must have been proven to have occurred before a person can be convicted of committing that crime.\n\nExample:\nA person cannot be tried for larceny unless it can be proven that property has been stolen. Likewise, in order for a person to be tried for arson it must be proven that a criminal act resulted in the burning of a property.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(527, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 18:03:13', '2016-06-18 18:03:13', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Malice Aforethought', 'The intention to kill or harm, which is held to distinguish unlawful killing from murder.\n\nMalice aforethought was the mens rea element of murder in 19th century America.', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL),
(528, '112913147917981568678', '2016-06-18 22:02:59', '2016-06-18 22:02:59', 1, NULL, NULL, 'Mens rea', 'The intention or knowledge of wrongdoing that constitutes part of a crime, as opposed to the action or conduct of the accused.\n\nTherefore, mens rea refers to the mental element of the offence that accompanies the actus reus. Under the traditional common law, the guilt or innocence of a person relied upon whether he had committed the crime (actus reus), and whether he intended to commit the crime (mens rea).', '{"tagsSingle":null}', 31, 0, 1, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Definitions & Examples', 'My Book', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, NULL);
